<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chief Negotiator Begins Consultations With EU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1703181494 Tallinn BNS in English 1619 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1703181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Mar 17, BNS -- Estonia is going to turn to 
the European Union [EU] for mediation in its talks with Moscow 
on the Russian troop withdrawal. 
  Estonia's chief negotiator for the talks with Russia, Vaino 
Reinart, began consultations on the issue in Brussels, a press 
release by the Estonian Foreign Ministry says. 
  The release issued today also says Estonia accepted Russia's 
proposal to hold the next round of talks in Moscow on Apr. 5-6, 
"despite a number of statements by Russian leaders, that are 
difficult to explain, on breaking off the negotiations and 
transfering the agreed final date for the withdrawal of troops." 
  The Estonian Foreign Ministry reminds that at the past round 
of the talks held in the seaside resort of Lohusalu near 
Tallinn, "the Russian side refused to pull out its remaining 
2,600 troops from Estonia by the earlier agreed deadline -- Aug. 
31, 1994. The Russian representatives also moved forward new 
conditions for the troop withdrawal and did not propose a date 
for the next round" of talks, the statement says. 
  Estonia also says that a "quick and powerful" reaction from 
the West had influenced Russia to continue talks and abide by 
the troop withdrawal deadline. 

</TEXT>

