<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference With Grachev </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703143694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1338 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Aleksey Agureyev and Vladimir </F>
Gondusov] 
  [Text] Moscow March 17 TASS -- Russia may join the 
"Partnership for Peace" initiative as early as the end of March, 
Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev told journalists on 
Thursday after finishing a meeting with United States Secretary 
of Defence William Perry. 
  "The groups of experts are already finishing their study of 
Russia's approach to joining 'Partnership for Peace,'" Grachev 
pointed out. "Basing our approach on Russia's particular needs, 
we will be ready to join the initiative already by the end of 
the month", he reported. The public will soon be able to have a 
look at the fundamental propositions of Russia's relationship 
with the partnership programme, he stated. 
  ITAR-TASS asked the defence ministers to comment on reports 
that the Pentagon in the near future intends to approve the 
allocation of funds to Russian and American corporations which 
will specialize in constructing housing for military personnel 
transferred to the reserves and in converting military 
enterprises to civilian production. 
  The American Defence Secretary announced that he would be 
discussing this topic with his Russian colleagues on Thursday 
and Friday. These talks should lead to the implementation of a 
joint programme which should require 60 to 100 million dollars 
in the next year, Perry said. 
  The defence secretary stated that his talks with Grachev 
focused on three global problems. First, the two sides had a 
good, positive discussion about the deepening of their working 
relations. Second, the partnership for peace initiative was 
discussed. Third, they discussed ways of improving 
Russian-American cooperation in Bosnia in order to speed up the 
peace process in that region, Perry explained. 
  During their discussion of the Bosnian question, the two 
sides agreed to cooperate as equal partners, he said. 
  The aim of their cooperation in bosnia is the continuation 
of 
talks with the Muslims, Croatians, and Bosnians in order to 
hasten the development of a peace agreement for the region, 
Perry said. Such an agreement would be in the interests of the 
United States, Russia, and all the countries in southeastern 
Europe. 
  Both ministers emphasized the importance of relations 
between 
their two departments in determining the character of relations 
between their respective countries. That is why a lot of 
attention during the meeting was paid to personal contacts 
between representatives of the two ministries, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

