<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses `Partnership' With Kozyrev </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703175994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1647 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaly Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Russia must be among the first and vigorous 
participants of partnership with NATO, Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev said in response to an Interfax question 
following his meeting with Secretary of Defense William Perry. 
  Kozyrev quoted Perry as saying that all countries willing to 
join NATO's Partnership for Peace program were equal. "It is 
also obvious, however, that Russia is a great power with its own 
interests. It would be strange if we were late arrivals," 
Kozyrev said meaning Partnership for Peace. 
  He said that the Russo-American cooperation must be equal, 
mutually beneficial and have clear cut goals. 
  "Pragmatism and usefulness must be the all-important 
factors. 
We should not be guided by ideological cliches. Like in a 
family, there are issues in the Russo-American relations which 
call for close coordination while in other fields every member 
of the family acts on his own trying not to harm the common 
interests," Kozyrev explained. He emphasized that neither the 
Russian nor the U.S. leaders intended to give up cooperation or 
partnership. 
  Answering another Interfax question, Kozyrev said that he 
had 
talked with Secretary of State Warren Christopher on the phone 
to discuss numerous international issues, notably the Middle 
East. He added that the UN Security Council would discuss a 
resolution on the Middle East Friday. 
  "This resolution must be passed urgently. The delay of its 
adoption hinders the resumption of Palestinian-Israeli talks," 
Kozyrev said. He emphasized that if the resolution were adopted 
Friday, Russian president's special envoy Viktor Posuvalyuk 
would go to Tunis to discuss with the PLO leader Yasir 'Arafat 
the specific day when the talks would resume. 
  Kozyrev said that the delay also provoked new tragedies and 
casualties in the Middle East. "It is important that the 
confrontation mechanism should not be allowed to gain momentum," 
he said. 
  He had also discussed Bosnia and Herzegovina with 
Christopher. "I expressed my view and the U.S. secretary of 
State agreed with it, that the Bosnian Moslems and Croats who 
intend to sign an agreement in Washington on March 18 on the 
setting up a federation should use this agreement as a tool for 
rapprochement and compromises with the third party, the Bosnian 
Serbs, rather than for opposing them jointly," Kozyrev said. He 
explained that Moscow would like to know if the federation was 
consistent with territorial integrity of Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
  "We hope that this agreement will be a step forward. But 
even at this point it is important to know what the next steps 
will be and how the Bosnian Serbs will be incorporated into it," 
Kozyrev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

