<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Welcomes U.S. Extension of Nuclear Moratorium </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703134094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1246 
GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 17 Mar -- The decision by the U.S. President 
to prolong the nuclear test moratorium for another year, up to 
September 1995, has been met with satisfaction in Russia. This 
was stated at a briefing today by Grigoriy Karasin, director of 
the department of information and the press of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry. 
  He stressed that Russia's position on this question remained 
unchanged. We were the initiators of the trilateral moratorium 
on nuclear tests, which is being observed de facto by Britain, 
too, and we recently stated once again our intention of 
continuing to adhere to it. At the same time we called on the 
other nuclear countries to do the same, the spokesman of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry stated. 
  In connection with this, he recalled that during the 
Russian-U.S. summit meeting in Moscow, Presidents Boris Yeltsin 
and Bill Clinton confirmed Russia's and the U.S. commitment to 
achieving within a very short period an international treaty on 
the total banning of nuclear tests. Karasin also noted the 
constructive atmosphere at the talks on this question, which are 
taking place at the disarmament conference in Geneva. 

</TEXT>

