<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry `Concerned' at DPRK Inspection Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703122794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1138 
GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Excerpt] Moscow, 17 Mar -- The Russian Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs is concerned that a group of experts from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) was unable fully to 
carry out the tasks of inspecting the nuclear facilities of the 
DPRK. A high-ranking source at the Russian Federation Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs told an ITAR-TASS correspondent this today. 
"This creates quite a serious situation," the diplomat said. 
  In his words, Russia is holding consultations on this matter 
with other IAEA members. He noted however that there is still 
some time before the meeting of the IAEA Board of Governors, set 
for 21 March, at which the results of the inspections are due to 
be discussed. Consequently, the situation could develop in a 
variety of ways, and the Russian Foreign Ministry will be 
following it carefully. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

