<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Outlines Plans for `Defense Area' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703213594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2109 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703213594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Valeriy Biryukov and Vadim </F>
Byrkin] 
  [Text] Kaliningrad March 18 TASS -- Russian Defence 
Minister Pavel Grachev announced on Thursday night an intention 
to create a special defence area in Russia's most western 
Kaliningrad region on the basis of the Baltic Fleet units and 
the 11th Guards Army stationed here. The minister came here on 
Thursday afternnon to discuss the issue with the region's 
military officers. 
  "The Kaliningrad region is different from all other Russian 
regions because of its geographic and enclave position", Grachev 
noted. "And the mobile grouping to be formed here is designed to 
ensure reliable protection of this territory against military 
threats from both the sea and land", he stressed. However, 
there will be no sweeping reductions in the officers' corps, the 
minister promised, therefore there are no grounds for concern. 
  Grachev informed officers about the progress of military 
reform. He also reported that some 20 new laws on armed forces 
were being drafted at the moment, "since many provisions of the 
laws passed by the former Supreme Soviet do no meet the Army's 
interests". Among the most important laws, the minister cited 
those on martial law, on military police, on courts martial. 
  The defence minister answered questions from the audience. 
After the meeting, well-known variety actors, who came from 
Moscow together with Grachev, gave a performance. 

</TEXT>

