<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Vladivostok Mayor </TI></H3>
<H4>   Official Says Reports of Riots Untrue </H4>
<F P=102> LD1703184494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1714 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The officer on duty in the Primorskoye Territory 
Interior Department told Interfax that the media reports of 
riots provoked in Vladivostok by the removal of mayor Viktor 
Cherepkov for bribe taking were untrue. 
  The officer also said that no gunmen had taken over the 
mayor's office Thursday. Cherepkov and his deputy had been 
evicted from the mayor's office Wednesday. 
  The officer said that as few as twenty, mostly elderly, 
supporters of Cherepkov, had been outside the city 
administration office in the early hours of Thursday. 
  Igor Lebedinets, deputy head of the territorial 
administration, told Interfax that the former mayor's supporters 
exaggerated the importance of the event. 
  An officer on duty in the Federal Counterintelligence 
Service 
said that the police, and not his agency, were handling the case. 
  The official representative of the territory in Moscow told 
Interfax that the situation in Vladivostok was quiet and 
Cherepkov had been removed from the mayor's office the day 
before. 
  Cherepkov could not be reached by phone. The territory 
representative said that Cherepkov had changed his telephone 
number on several occasions during his tenure of office. Now he 
probably simply did not want to lift the receiver. The official 
said that the exact whereabouts of Cherepkov were unknown. He 
had not been arrested but had been told not to leave the city. 

</TEXT>

