<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Vladivostok Mayor </TI></H3>
<H4>   Public Prosecutor Begins Investigating Mayor </H4>
<F P=102> LD1703165294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1630 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow March 17 TASS -- Acting Russian Public 
Prosecutor Aleksey Ilyushenko ordered one of his senior 
investigators on Thursday to probe into the case of Vladivostok 
Mayor Viktor Cherepkov accused of bribe-taking, the press centre 
of the public prosecutor's office said. 
  Criminal proceedings against Cherepkov were instituted in 
February 1994 on charges of bribery. 
  The decision followed the second day of unrest in the city. 
On Wednesday, armed riot police stormed the mayor's office and 
told Cherepkov and his closest aides they were dismissed from 
office. First Deputy Mayor Vladimir Gilgenberg, who put up 
resistance, was literally carried out from the building by 
police. 
  This was the second armed invasion of the city 
administration 
building. The first one occurred on the night of February 13, 
and was prompted, according to an official version, by the need 
to question Cherepkov on receiving a bribe from a certain 
Volkov. The mayor then remained at power thanks to public 
support. 
  Supporters of the toppled mayor, including a group of voters 
who nominated him to the regional council, have announced that 
Cherepkov's toppling was an act of open arbitrariness and a 
gross violation of human rights. They said they would hold acts 
of protest, including hunger strikes at the regional 
administration headquarters. 

</TEXT>

