<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Gives First Approval to Law on Peacekeeping Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1703134094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 17 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK1703134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Yelena Tregubova report under the "Project" rubric: "State </F>
Duma Deputies Intend To Legitimize `Russia's Peacemaker 
Activities'"] 
  [Text] Yesterday, the State Duma passed in the first 
reading a draft federal law "On the Procedure for the Provision 
of Russian Federation Military and Civilian Personnel for the 
Participation in Operations to Maintain or Restore International 
Peace and Security, and in Other Types of Peacekeeping 
Activities." 
  According to Defense Committee figures, at the moment, one 
Russian battalion of 1,200 men is on the territory of 
Yugoslavia, four battalions numbering 1,778 men are in Moldova, 
one regiment of 503 men is in Georgia, and one division of 5,982 
men is in Tajikistan. In addition to these military formations, 
according to committee chairman Sergey Yushenkov, 87 Russian 
military observers are taking part in UN peacekeeping 
operations. Georgiy Kondratyev, Russian Federation deputy 
defense minister, told parliamentarians yesterday, however, that 
16,500 Russian soldiers are present in the so-called "hot spots" 
today. Interestingly, General Kondratyev urged that on no 
account "a limit be set" on the permitted participation of 
Russian Federation servicemen in such actions. 
  The presenters of official reports agreed that "peacekeeping 
forces" should be withdrawn from the jurisdiction of Russia's 
Armed Forces and subordinated to the Ministry for Emergency 
Situations. 
  It was decided to forward the draft federal law to the 
president, the deputy factions, the groups and commissions "for 
the preparation of proposals and remarks." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

