<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Hearings on State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703154294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1406 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 17 TASS -- The Russian Parliament's 
upper house, the Federation Council, decided to continue 
hearings on the situation in the zone under state of emergency 
rule in North Ossetia and Ingushetia, House Speaker Vladimir 
Shumeyko told reporters after the Federation Council's 
closed-door meeting. According to him, "the conflict between 
the Republics of North Ossetia and Ingushetia is extremely 
acute, since one of the main human rights, the right to live, is 
being violated". 
  Shumeyko reported that lawmakers instructed the Federation 
Council chairman to set up a special commission for further 
investigation into this issue. After this, the commission is to 
submit its proposals for the president's consideration. 
Lawmakers think it necessary to hold an enlarged meeting of the 
Security Council with the participation of the special 
commission so that the next meeting of the upper house could 
pass the final decision. 
  The Federation Council chairman emphasised that this 
mechanism of decision-making was the most expedient. In his 
opinion, many decisions have been taken earlier, but all of them 
were never implemented. Therefore, Shumeyko stressed, "it is 
critical that all the three branches of power (the Federation 
Council, the president and the government) discuss this issue 
and make a joint decision". 
  The upper house speaker also told reporters that deputies 
adopted at their meeting an appeal to the peoples of Ingushetia 
and North Ossetia. The document stresses the need "to lay down 
arms and solve the problems piled over many years by peaceful 
means". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

