<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze To Clear `Drug Addicts' From His Staff </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703180994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1652 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy, edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Twenty eight members of Eduard Shevardnadze's office 
were subjected to an unusual procedure on Wednesday. They began 
to undergo medical tests designed to reveal drug abusers. 
  As Interfax learned from the Georgian leader's aides, state 
counsellors, chiefs of departments and ordinary members of the 
office had their urine tested, showed doctors their blood 
vessels and answered questions. All this aims to rid government 
institutions of drug addicts. According to an official, such 
examinations will be regular. 
  On February 5th Eduard Shevardnadze signed a decree which 
said that "the growing trend toward drug addiction jeopardizes 
people's health, poses a threat to national security, and 
discredits government institutions." In this connection a 
governmental commission was formed. It is led by Deputy Premier 
Irakly Menagarishvili. 
  The check-up will spread to other government institutions, 
above all to the Defence and Interior Ministries, some of whose 
members have been caught abusing or trafficking narcotics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

