<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   One More Border Incident Involves Russians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1703160394 Tallinn BNS in English 1057 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1703160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Mar 17, BNS -- One more border incident 
involving armed Russian servicemen occurred on the 
Lithuanian-Russian border this week. 
  An armed Russian convoy escorting governmental mail was 
taken-off a Moscow-Kaliningrad train because the Russians did 
not have permission to carry weapons on Lithuanian territory. 
Lithuanian border guards disarmed the Russian soldiers and 
handed them over to the police. 
  The convoys explained that they were supposed to deliver the 
mail by plane, but their flight was canceled and they had to 
take a train. The Russians were given back their weapons and 
were allowed to board another train. 
  Colonel Pranas Dragunaitis, head of the Lithuanian Border 
Defense Service, discussed the incident with representatives of 
the Russian troops stationed in the Kaliningrad region. 
Dragunaitis emphasized the need to put a stop to violations of 
armed servicemen transit regulations. 
  The Lithuanian official said the rules of transporting 
weapons through Lithuanian territory must be strictly observed. 
He noted that Lithuanian border guards will never make any 
concessions to anybody and will always act in accordance with 
the law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

