<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Far Eastern Space Port To Have Four Launch Sites </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703163494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1323 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS corespondent Veronika Romanenkova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 17 TASS -- Although work is just 
beginning in Russia's new Far Eastern spaceport of Svobodniy, 
specialists are thinking about its future uses. 
  According to Aleksey Krysanov, department chief at the 
General Machine-Building Design Bureau, which is charged with 
designing the new space port, the feasibility study of the new 
space centre will be completed before the end of 1994. 
  The preliminary plans provide for these of first two and 
then 
five silos for launching light booster rockets of the Rokot 
(Rumbler) type and two new launch pads for the lift-off of the 
heavy Angara-24 boosters. 
  No huge outlays are required for the first launches of the 
Rokot missiles -- specialists will do with two of the several 
tens of silos left behind by the military missile division which 
was disbanded under the START II agreement last autumn after 
serving the country's defenses since 1968. The silos, measuring 
more than 20 meters in depth and 4.2 meters across, some 
equipment and the control room as well as the life-support 
system were also left intact after the military took away their 
"toys." Some new equipment has to be installed and launches for 
peaceful purposes can begin. 
  Rokot missiles can be launched from the silos. Two launches 
have already been effected from Baykonur. After some 
modifications the missiles, earlier used for defence purposes, 
will lift off light military and civilian satellites. 
  Aleksey Krysanov stressed that the missile division used to 
occupy an area of several tens of square kilometers. The new 
spaceport will need less land. The remainder will be 
re-cultivated before being returned to civilian authorities. 

</TEXT>

