<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pensions To Increase in Line With Growth in Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703141794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0915 
GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 17 Mar -- In the first six months of 1994 it 
is envisaged that a form of compensation should be retained by 
increasing pensions in line with the growth in consumer prices. 
From 1 February compensation to pensioners is to be increased 
from 11,700 rubles to 20,000 rubles and from 1 May to 29,600 
rubles. This was reported today at a session of the Russian 
Federation Government Presidium by Vasiliy Barchuk, chairman of 
the board of Russia's pension fund, during an examination of the 
draft budget of the fund for the first six months of 1994. 
  He explained that the fund's draft budget presupposes that 
its income amounts to almost 17 trillion rubles, and its 
expenditure to approximately 16 trillion rubles. Of the 
budget's income, 16.1 trillion rubles derive from insurance 
contributions from employers and citizens, and 784 billion 
rubles come from the republican budget. 
  In his speech Vasiliy Barchuk drew attention to the "need to 
ensure the timely payment of state pensions, otherwise we will 
have serious social conflicts." 
  In this connection Viktor Chernomyrdin stated that "the 
government cannot allow pension payments to be overdue; we have 
to act in a precise manner here." The chairman of the 
government has warned leaders of the regions which delay 
payments to the pension fund that this practice is inadmissible. 
At the suggestion of Viktor Chernomyrdin, the draft budget of 
the Russian Federation pension fund for the first six months of 
1994 was approved as a whole by the presidium of the government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

