<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cited on U.S.-Russian Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1703104194 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 17 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1703104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Pogorelyy report: "Both Partners and Competitors"] </F>
  [Text] In the new world, under radically changed 
conditions, Russia and America might be not only partners but 
also competitors, and each country might have its own strategic 
aims in international policy which do not coincide with the 
other side's interests. U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry 
made such an admission on the eve of his visit to Moscow. 
  The Pentagon head declared that there should be active 
cooperation with Russia in those cases where the two countries' 
interests coincide and that mutual attempts to act independently 
should be perceived calmly when such interests do not coincide. 
Americans should also be prepared, however, for the fact that 
the strategic aims of Russia and the United States might also 
contradict each other. 
  Precisely in order to prevent such a turn, the United States 
must give all possible support to Russia's democratic processes 
and peace-loving steps, the defense secretary emphasized. Among 
the main areas of cooperation in the military and 
military-political sphere between the two countries he 
particularly singled out cooperation in destroying chemical 
arsenals and part of the nuclear arsenals, in combating the 
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, and in converting 
defense production. The Pentagon chief named as examples of 
direct cooperation along military lines the exercise planned for 
this summer by Russian and U.S. peacemaking contingents -- the 
27th Motorized Rifle Division and the 3d Mechanized Division 
respectively. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16707 </DOCNO>
