<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Holds Hearings on Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lukin Against Joining </H4>
<F P=102> LD1703115594 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
0900 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma is holding hearings into the 
Partnership for Peace program today. 
  [Correspondent Dmitriy Vinsker] Representatives of the 
foreign and defense ministries who spoke at the hearings 
insisted on the need for Russia to join in this program. In 
their opinion, Russia outside the Partnership for Peace program 
will be on the path of self-isolation, but if Russia joins it 
can develop the program in ways which are necessary for Moscow. 
  Vladimir Lukin, chairman of the Duma's International 
Committee, spoke against joining. According to him the idea of 
the program is good but, in his words, the devil is hidden in 
the details, and these details, as Lukin stressed, incidentally 
just like the positive and negative sides of the program, are 
insufficiently thought through. It is worth noting that 
Vladimir Lukin's stance is shared, to a lesser or greater 
degree, by virtually all the deputies of the lower chamber. 
  Dmitriy Vinsker, Ekho Moskvy, the State Duma. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

