<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Cooperation Accord Signed With Romania </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803120194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1708 
GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1803120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Nikolay Morozov] </F>
  [Text] Bucharest, 17 Mar -- An agreement on cooperation 
between the defense ministries of Romania and Ukraine was signed 
today in Bucharest by Gheorghe Tinca and Vitaliy Radetskyy, the 
heads of the military departments of the two countries. [passage 
omitted] 
  During the talks, issues of regional safety were discussed 
in 
depth, Ukrainian Defense Minister Army General Vitaliy Radetskyy 
said in an interview to an ITAR-TASS correspondent. We believe 
that the proposal in the sphere of ensuring regional safety, 
which President Leonid Kravchuk made in Budapest last year, and 
the "Partnership for Peace" program are interconnected. The 
adoption of the Ukrainian proposal may become the first step in 
tackling the problems of the "Partnership for Peace". 
  We regard talk about isolating Russia from these processes 
as 
unrealistic, the head of the Ukrainian military department 
stressed. Russia is a great neighboring state, and a common 
historical past unites Ukraine and Russia. We treat Russia with 
great respect and are ready for bilateral cooperation with it. 
  As to the prospects of joining NATO, in accordance with the 
decision of the parliament, as is known, Ukraine is not a member 
of any bloc. Military-political and military-technical issues 
connected with it are being worked on at the moment, and the 
Defense Ministry proposals will be submitted to the new 
parliament that has the prerogative to make a corresponding 
decision. 
  The territorial issues of North Bukovina, the south of 
Bessarabia, and Zmeinyy Ostrov were not raised at the talks in 
Bucharest, V.Radetskiy noted. We recognize Romania's 
territorial integrity, and Romania fully recognizes the 
territorial integrity of Ukraine. The Romanian side stressed 
that some would have liked to raise this issue for the purpose 
of causing the two neighboring countries to quarrel or of 
creating tension between them. However, we must proceed from 
the official stand of the heads of state. That is why Ukraine 
and Romania do not lay any claims on each other. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

