<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rumors About Attempt on Yeltsin's Life in Sochi Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1803085094 Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY in Russian 18 Mar 94 p 
14 </F>

<F P=103> MK1803085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Mikhail Lashch report: "Rumors About Attempt on </F>
President's Life. There Has Been No Attempt"] 
  [Text] Yesterday rumors spread in Moscow about an attempt 
on President Boris Yeltsin's life. KOMMERSANT-DAILY's 
correspondent turned to the Russian Main Security Administration 
[MSA] for comment. According to MSA information, what gave rise 
to the rumor was the following event. 
  Andrey Oligov, press secretary of the president's Main 
Security Administration, said that on 15 March security officers 
at the president's summer house detained a 45-year-old local 
resident who tried to sneak into the compound. The intruder 
said that he entered the guarded territory because he was 
looking for his missing son, a serviceman. This information was 
checked and proved to be correct; afterward the detainee was 
released. 
  According to KOMMERSANT-DAILY information, yesterday at 1530 
Aleksandr Korzhakov, chief of the presidential security service, 
called the Kremlin from Sochi to say that no other incidents 
have occurred on the territory of the presidential residence in 
Sochi. 
  The president continues his vacation in Sochi; his health is 
normal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

