<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Blames Armenians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1903204694 Paris AFP in English 1953 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1903204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 19 (AFP) -- At least 12 people were 
killed and 61 others injured, eight seriously, in an explosion 
Saturday in a crowded subway station in Baku, Azerbaijani 
authorities reported. 
  Fuad Akhundov, a presidential spokesman contacted by AFP, 
said that the explosion was caused by a delayed-action bomb. 
  The blast ripped through two coaches of a train in the 
January 20 subway station, the Azerbaijani news agency 
ASSA-IRADA said. First the head wagon, then the second 
exploded, both being engulfed by fire, it said. 
  "According to all probabilities, it was the Armenians," 
Akhundov said. 
  Azerbaijani troops have been fighting a six-year war against 
Armenian separatists from Nagorno-Karabakh, a territory 
populated mostly by Armenians but controlled by Baku. 
  More than 20,000 people have been killed in the fighting 
since 1988 and the Armenians were widely seen in Baku as likely 
perpetrators of any bombing. 
  However, no explosive device had been discovered by Saturday 
evening to back the bomb thesis. 
  A local journalist reached by phone said that about 100 
wounded people were evacuated from the station which was closed 
by police shortly after the blast. 
  Tensions have been running high in Baku, the Azerbaijani 
capital, in recent weeks after security forces began a crackdown 
against opposition forces supporting exiled former president 
Abulfaz Elchibey. 
  Several members of the Popular Front headed by Elchibey have 
been arrested and police have staged raids on the headquarters 
of the opposition party. 
  After the blast Saturday, Azerbaijani President Geydar 
Aliyev 
called an emergency meeting of internal security officials, but 
the outcome of the meeting was not immediately known. 
  The explosion occurred around 1:00 p.m. (0800 GMT) in the 
subway station located in the northern district of the city and 
named "January 20" after the 1990 crackdown in Azerbaijan by 
Soviet troops. 
  At least 170 people died in the crackdown ordered by Moscow 
to quash weeks of violence between Armenians and Azeris in the 
northern suburb of Sumgait. 
  A diplomat in Baku said the number of casualties was 
probably 
increased by the fact that people were out in force to go 
shopping ahead of the new year celebrations Monday (as 
calculated by the old, pre-Islamic calendar). 
  Another explosion took place a month ago on a train coming 
into Azerbaijan from Russia, without causing any casualties. 
Responsibility for the explosion was not established. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

