<H3> <TI>   Local Media Carry `Letters of Support' for Karimov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803181394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1649 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: By diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] The president's press service had a set of letters 
of support for Islam Karimov published in local media. 
  Tashkent residents wrote that whatever Uzbekistan had 
accomplished was the result of the president's resolute 
activities "for the great cause of making the republic one of 
the most advanced countries of the world." The authors of the 
letters "as Uzbek subjects" wanted to stand by the Uzbek leader 
to help him. They emphasized that Karimov "worked 
self-sacrificingly for peace and quiet in the Republic." 
  The letters expressed indignation over "the activities of a 
bunch of slanderers who fled Uzbekistan and smuggled into it the 
publications that libel the Motherland." 
  The authors of the letters called on the president to put an 
end to the activities of those who smuggled "slanderous pieces" 
into the Republic and "could not reconcile to Uzbekistan's 
future as a great state." 

</TEXT>

