<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sign Defense Conversion Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1903133294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1308 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1903133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty 19 March, TASS -- U.S. Secretary of Defence 
William Perry, who is currently in Kazakhstan on a working 
visit, was received in the republican Ministry of Defence on 
Saturday. Mr. Perry also attended a session of the joint 
Kazakhstan-American committee on defence industry conversion to 
civilian production. 
  The meetings, and the talks with President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev several hours earlier, resulted in the signing of an 
agreement on the conversion of the Kazakhstan defence industry 
to civilian production. 
  The agreement is actually a supplement to the earlier 
reached 
accord on the dismantling of the SS-18 missile silos and ensures 
an influx of an aggregate of 70 million U.S. dollars to the 
republic for defence industry conversion needs. 
  These documents are intended to ensure the dismantling of 
combat nuclear missile systems based in Kazakhstan and convert 
them to suit civilian and peaceful purposes, and additional 
training of the military personnel subject to demobilisation. 
  U.S. businesses are to be invited to help the defence 
industry conversion effort. In particular, a number of American 
companies will be involved in the reconstruction of appropriate 
enterprises for them to change over to the manufacture of 
consumer goods. 
  Mr. Perry and his party are to leave for Baykonur cosmodrome 
on 20 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

