<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increase in Russian-Speakers Leaving Kyrgyzstan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003152194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1334 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2003152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The head of Kyrgyzstan's parliament said the outflow 
of Russian speakers from the Central Asian republic was 
seriously harming its culture, education and economy. 
  Medetkan Sherimkulov told INTERFAX on Saturday that 100,000 
Russian-speakers had already left Kyrgyzstan, which has a 
Russian-speaking community of about 1 million, or 20 percent of 
the total population. He said more Russian speakers were 
leaving than were coming in, the gap permanently increasing. As 
a result, the republic is losing much of its engineering and 
research personnel, many teachers and high-skilled workers, he 
said. 
  Sherimkulov believes that what forces so many Russian 
speakers to go away is fear of possible future instability and 
the low wages, which on average are less than half those in 
Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

