<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discuss Transdniester Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803204094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1718 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian president's official representative, 
Ambassador Vladlen Vasev, has confirmed Moscow's position of 
standing for "the territorial integrity of Moldova and the 
overcoming of all discord by political means." 
  The Moldovan president's press service announced that 
Moldovan President Mircea Snegur and Russian Ambassador Vasev 
had met on Friday. They agreed that settlement of the 
Transdniestrian issue would contribute to restoration of 
stability in the region, which conformed with the interests of 
the population. 
  Moldovan President Snegur stressed that the democratic 
parliamentary elections and the sociological poll, during which 
most of the population had spoken for independence of Moldova, 
were the basis for normalization of the situation in Moldova's 
eastern regions. Namely, Snegur favored granting a special 
legal status with a high level of autonomy to this region. 

</TEXT>

