<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Denies Telephones Cut </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103163994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1436 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Valeriy Grishin, first deputy head of the Russian 
government press service, strongly denied rumors that telephones 
had been deliberately cut off in the government residence. 
  He told Interfax Monday that the telephone lines in the 
building had been put out of order by hot water from a broken 
pipeline. As a result, some telephones were cut off and some 
only receive calls from the city, while calling from them is 
hopeless. 
  Officials in the Communications Ministry confirmed for 
Interfax the fact of a breakdown in the pipeline which resulted 
in disruption of telephone links with the government 
headquarters. 
  City utility services on Monday intended to pump water out 
of 
the trench where the cable is laid. The cable itself is to be 
dried out Tuesday and the damage repaired. If need be, the 
entire lines will be replaced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

