<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Yeltsin Activities in Sochi </TI></H3>
<H4>   Approves Krasnodar Governor's Proposals </H4>
<F P=102> PM1803171694 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 18 Mar 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1803171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Bulygin report: "President Rests and Solves </F>
State Problems"] 
  [Text] Krasnodar Kray -- During his short vacation in 
Sochi, Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin has spent more than 12 hours a 
day untying "Gordian knots." He is doing this by checking his 
plans against the opinions of regional leaders. 
  The meeting between the head of state and Kuban Governor 
Nikolay Yegorov lasted several hours. The latter admitted that 
he was pleasantly surprised by the president's knowledge of the 
state of affairs in Krasnodar Kray. That is why problems 
relating to the Kuban's economy and social and cultural spheres 
were discussed without any preamble. 
  The subject of the head of state's special concern was the 
development of the agrarian sector. The president focused 
attention on the need for more careful preparation and organized 
conduct of spring field work, and approved the measures being 
adopted by the kray leadership in this sphere. 
  Programs drawn up in the kray for the development of 
industry, construction, culture, the social sphere, and the 
fight against organized crime, and approaches to strengthening 
Russia's land and maritime borders with the Transcaucasus states 
and to the stationing of forces re-stationed in Kuban from 
nearby and more distant foreign countries, also met with 
Yeltsin's support. The president agreed with the proposals made 
by the head of the kray administration aimed at solving 
questions of interethnic relations, and he approved of the 
governor's intention to introduce a visa system for crossing the 
borders of Krasnodar Kray. B. Yeltsin advised Yegorov to 
present the relevant proposals to the federal authorities. 

</TEXT>

