<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Official Responds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803171794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1123 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kirill Ignatyev, member of the Russia's Choice 
parliamentary group coordinating committee and member of the 
parliamentary information committee, described the setting up of 
an Accord in the Name of Russia movement as the emergence of 
"Rutskoy's small party." Rutskoy is likely to run in the next 
presidential race. 
  Ignatyev told Interfax that it was significant that the 
appeal to Russia's citizens which declared the setting up of the 
movement had not been signed by the Liberal Democratic Party 
whose leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy will "beyond any doubt" run 
for presidency. 
  Ignatyev took note of the fact that the appeal had not been 
signed by opposition figures such as Viktor Anpilov and Viktor 
Tyulkin, the leader of the Russian Communist Party, a rival of 
the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, headed by Gennady 
Zyuganov, who did join the Accord in the Name of Russia. 
  Ignatyev thought that the setting up of a new movement 
reflected a deep split among counter-reformists and the tendency 
to build up various groups around presidential candidates. 
  He admitted, however, that "even though just a small number 
of counter-reformists rallied around the Accord, we must 
understand that the setting up of the so-called Rutskoy's party 
compels the democrats to consolidate." Russia's Choice would 
step up work on the setting up of its own party, he said. 

</TEXT>

