<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov on Progress of Work on `Memorandum of Accord' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103173794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1600 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 21 TASS -- "Five expert groups which 
are preparing concrete sections of the memorandum of accord -- 
on the economy, regional and national policy, security, law and 
culture and political life -- are completing their work on the 
document," Russian Presidential Chief of Staff Sergey Filatov 
said. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Monday, Filatov said that 
public accord is achievable on the basis of the memorandum. He 
expressed bewilderment over the attempts by some politicians to 
set up a new political bloc, "Accord for Russia." The 
participation of Constitutional Court member Valeriy Zorkin in 
this bloc revives the dispute about his inappropriate political 
activity which has already cost him his post of Constitutional 
Court chairman. 
  "There cannot be two consensuses. There can be only one 
consensus," Filatov said. Additionally, the idea proposed by 
Communist leader Gennadiy Zyuganov, Zorkin, former 
vice-president Aleksandr Rutskoy and others looks "militant." 
"One has to dislike his nation particularly strong in order to 
whip up fear in society," he added. 
  President Boris Yeltsin's senior adviser Georgiy Satarov 
said 
that a joint team of experts will hold a meeting on Wednesday to 
discuss the memorandum. On Thursday, the text of the document 
will be handed over to Yeltsin who is expected to return from 
vacation by the end of the week. "The achievement of civic 
accord is not a one- time process," he said. It is open to all 
who want to join it, Satarov said. 

</TEXT>

