<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rally Supports Mayor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803151894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1459 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Eduard Popov] </F>
  [Text] Vladivostok March 18 TASS -- A rally in support of 
ex-Vladivostok Mayor Viktor Cherepkov was held on Thursday night 
on Vladivostok central square. The ex-mayor's supporters 
estimated his removal from the post as a "gross violation of 
human rights, non-observation of the Russian constitution and 
laws and the return to 1937". 
  The rally attended by several hundred persons adopted a 
resolution to demand that the higher instances remove Maritime 
governor Yevgeniy Nazdratenko and Maritime procurator Valeriy 
Vasilenko from their posts. 
  A reason for the demand of Vasilenko's resignation is "the 
lack of the territorial procurator's office control over 
lawfulness and permission of the eviction of the legitimately- 
elected mayor from his study with the use of force". 
  According to reliable sources, Viktor Cherepkov has gone on 
a 
hunger strike and is staying at home. 
  As for ex-mayor's Deputy Vladimir Gilgenberg, pushed out 
from 
the mayor's office, he has not been produced any documents to 
substantiate his removal from the mayor deputy post. Asked 
about reasons for this situation, senior assistant of the 
Maritime Territorial Procurator Veniamin Chichayev told 
ITAR-TASS "It is not the business of the procurator's office, 
and acting Vladivostok Mayor Konstantin Tolstoshein has the 
right to choose his deputies himself". 
  Criminal proceedings instituted against Viktor Cherepkov on 
charge of major bribe-taking in February 1994 have been taken 
over by the Russian procurator general's office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

