<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Decree Suspends Leningrad Region Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803211594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2009 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 18 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin signed a decree "On suspension of a resolution of the 
Leningrad Regional Government," the Presidential Press Service 
Reports. The decree runs as follows: 
  "Bearing in mind, the resolution of the Leningrad Regional 
Government of February 7, 1994, #5 'on measures for preparations 
and holding of elections of the Leningrad Regional Legislative 
Assembly, local government bodies and a regional referendum on 
draft rules of the Leningrad region' in part of holding the 
regional referendum on draft rules of the Leningrad region 
violates Paragraph 2 of Article 66 of the Russian Constitution, 
under which rules of a territory, a region, a federal city, an 
autonomous region and an autonomous district shall be adopted by 
a legislative (representative) body of corresponding subject of 
the Russian Federation and being guided by Paragraph 2 of 
Article 85 of the Russian Constitution, I resolute: 
  - to suspend the validity of the resolution of the Leningrad 
Regional Government of February 7, 1994, #5 `On measures for 
preparations and holding of elections of the Legislative 
Assembly of the Leningrad region, local government bodies and a 
regional referendum on draft rules of the Leningrad region' in 
part of holding the regional referendum on draft rules of the 
Leningrad region". 
  The Leningrad regional Government scheduled for March 20, 
1994, a regional referendum on draft rules of the Leningrad 
region. 
  This decision was protested against the regional procurator 
as not corresponding to Article 66 of the Russian Constitution. 
Under this article, such legal acts shall be adopted by 
legislative (representative) body of a corresponding federation 
subject. However, such a body has not been elected in the 
Leningrad region. The elections of the Regional Legislative 
Assembly are scheduled for March 20. 
  The regional government rejected the protest of the 
procurator, and the president used his constitutional right to 
suspend the regional government's resolution on the referendum, 
although he has nothing against the rules themselves. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

