<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev on Future Role of Antiaircraft Defenses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103115994 Moscow 2x2 Television in Russian 1130 GMT 21 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow 2x2 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev has denied 
reports of future cuts in antiaircraft defense troops. Instead, 
in conversation with journalists he said that the military 
department has examined the issue of the expediency of 
continuing to preserve the present antiaircraft defense 
structure. In Grachev's opinion, under current conditions there 
is no need for antiaircraft defense forces to cover all sites. 
Therefore a decision has been taken on protecting only main 
sites, in particular nuclear and hydroelectric power stations, 
defense industry factories, and state institutions throughout 
Russia. Grachev also reported that the military department 
intends to get rid of antiquated antiaircraft defense systems. 

</TEXT>

