<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on New Arms Exports Corporation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803204594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2012 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 18 TASS -- "The creation of the 
"Rossvooruzhenie" corporation is another step taken by Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin with the aim of fostering the Russian 
statehood and Russia's position in the world community" said 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev on Friday night, 
addressing the ceremony of the inauguration of a new state 
corporation "Rossvooruzhenie" for exports and imports of weapons. 
  The corporation was established in accordance with the 
Russian president's decree and on the basis of three former 
foreign trade associations. The task of the newly established 
corporation is to ensure state monopoly over exports and imports 
of weapons and defence hardware for the development of military 
and technical cooperation with foreign countries. 
  Kozyrev pointed out that the development of military 
cooperation with foreign countries promotes the growth of 
Russian industry, creation of work places and higher industrial 
output. At the same time, the development of such cooperation 
is a tangible contribution to strengthening peace and stability 
both in the world and in separate regions. 
  Any country which supports and develops such cooperation 
with 
Russia, can count on Russia's diplomatic support. At the same 
time, by developing such cooperation, we expect an adequate 
attitude from our foreign partners and honest attitude in trade, 
the Russian minister said. 
  Weapons as an item for exports cannot be regarded as a 
conventional commodity, and therefore, Russia seeks to give 
weapons trade a civilized character. "We shall see to it that 
weapons do not spread over the world, and primarily, its most 
destabilizing specimen and weapons of mass destruction," the 
Russian foreign minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

