<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karelian Premier Quits Election for Parliament Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803173394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1123 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sergey Blinnikov, prime minister of Karelia, a 
constituent republic of the Russian Federation, has dropped out 
of the race for chairmanship of the parliament. The election is 
scheduled for April 17. He is expected to explain his decision 
to the Supreme Soviet's session to be held in Petrozavodsk 
Friday. 
  The incumbent Chairman Viktor Stepanov who is also running 
for this position told Interfax that he regretted what happened. 
He said that the interest of the electorate would not be met if 
there was no alternative candidate. He also said that he did 
not intend to quit the race and would not do so unless there 
were important personal reasons. He described his rival's 
decision as disrespectful of the electorate and thought that the 
opposition would say that there was no choice in the election. 
  Observers noted that while 5,000 signatures were needed to 
register a candidate in the election, Blinnikov's supporters had 
collected 6,000 while Stepanov's had a total of 15,500 
signatures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

