<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Ossetian President for Normal Relations with Neighbors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1903210594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1331 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1903210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz, 19 Mar -- "The parliamentary hearings 
at the Federal Assembly and the closed session of the Federation 
Council are yet another attempt to settle relations between 
North Ossetia and Ingushetia by peaceful means, North Ossetian 
President Akhsarbek Galazov said today. 
  Speaking at a republican government session, members of the 
North Ossetian Supreme Soviet Presidium, and heads of local 
self-government bodies of Vladikavkaz and regions, he stressed 
that the Republic of North Ossetia was extremely interested in 
establishing normal relations with all its neighbors in North 
Caucasus and the Transcaucasus. However, the multi-ethnic 
people of the republic denounce the use of force in resolving 
these issues. The issue of refugee return to Prigorodnyy Rayon 
should not be forced either. This problem should be tackled by 
conciliatory commissions on the basis of the Kislovodsk 
Agreements. 
  The North Ossetian president reiterated his readiness to 
meet 
Ingush President Ruslan Aushev to discuss the settlement of 
relations between the peoples of the two republics. 
  Speaking about the position taken by the commission of 
deputies that worked in the state of emergency zone and who 
reported to the parliament on the results of its trip to North 
Caucasus, Akhsarbek Galazov said that it had gathered vast 
material but had made hasty and nonobjective conclusions which 
may cause the situation in the region to explode and may bring 
to naught all earlier peace-making efforts by the North Ossetian 
leadership and the interim administration. 
  He added that at the proposal of Russian Federation Council 
Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko, a special commission would be set up 
to draw up objective solutions aimed at settling the situation 
in the conflict zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

