<H3> <TI>   Extends Assembly Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103132094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1143 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mayor of St. Petersburg Anatoliy Sobchak has 
extended the elections to the City Assembly, held on March 20, 
by another 24 hours. 
  Sobchak did so just 90 minutes before voting was to end, 
when 
it became clear that the elections were a failure. According to 
the city electoral commission, only 21.532000060100f the electors came 
to the polling stations (elections will be considered valid if 
252000060100f the electors take part in voting). 
  The electoral commission believes that a second round of 
elections must be held. As each seat in the City Assembly is 
contested by about 15 candidates, it is unlikely that any of 
them will accrue the required 5010006040lus 1 vote. 
  Sobchak has made an amendment in the provision on elections 
according to which a candidate shall be considered elected 
during the first round if he receives a majority of the votes 
irrespective of the number of voters. 

</TEXT>

