<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Limits on Ostankino TV May `Create Rift' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2103104194 Tallinn BNS in English 1312 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2103104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Mar 19, BNS -- Ending the transmission of 
broadcasts of the Ostankino TV channel in Estonia would create 
an irreparable rift between Estonia's Russian-speaking 
population and the government, an appeal delivered to the 
government by the country's Russian Assembly says. 
  The Estonian Government ruled to cut back from March 11 the 
time that Ostankino broadcasts are available to viewers in 
Estonia, after the Moscow television company failed to pay for 
the transmission of its program on Estonia's national network. 
The government ruling says the broadcasts will be cut off 
completely from March 28 if Ostankino by that date has not 
signed a new agreement with the Estonian Telecommunications 
Company or has paid its debts for the last months. 
  The step would negatively affect the Russian-speakers' 
loyalty to the Estonia Government, Estonia's Russian Assembly 
says. The document also says that the assembly has already 
called on the respective Russian institutions to resolve the 
financial problems connected with the transmission of Ostankino 
broadcasts. 
  The assembly suggests that the Ostankino program be 
transmitted in Estonia via a cable network. The representative 
body says a respective agreement together with a financing 
project should be signed at the level of the two countries' 
governments. 
  Ostankino owes to the Estonian company about 105,000 German 
marks for the transmission of its broadcasts in 1993, plus some 
80,000 German marks for January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

