<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves Plan To Raise Fuel Excise Taxes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2103100894 Tallinn BNS in English 1730 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2103100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Baltic Business Weekly" feature] </F>
  [Text] The Estonian Cabinet approved March 17 a bill on 
increasing the fuel excise tax rates up to two times from the 
present. The draft now enters the parliament. 
  The draft legislation proposes raising the excise tax on 
gasoline from the present 0.40 kroons per liter to 0.80 kroons 
for ordinary gasoline, and to 0.60 kroons for gasoline 
containing less than 0.013 grams of lead per liter. 
  Introduction of different rates is aimed at encouraging car 
owners to use fuel less detrimental to the environment. 
  The excise tax on diesel fuel is to be hiked from the 
current 
0.25 kroons to 0.50 kroons per liter. Rates for aircraft fuel, 
liquid gas and lubricants are to remain the same. 
  The government has said the step is mainly due to the need 
to 
earn an estimated additional 21.8 million kroons into the state 
coffers to pay higher pensions from April. 
  A representative at the Finance Ministry said the Estonian 
Oil Association, a body connecting the country's fuel companies, 
had agreed to the motion. 
  The Oil Association's managing director, Mart Kutsar, told 
BNS his association had not approved of the planned step. But 
he also said in an interview with the ARIPAEV business newspaper 
that despite not approving of the step the association still 
understood that the hike was inevitable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16814 </DOCNO>
