<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry on Integration Into European Transit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2103103994 Tallinn BNS in English 1312 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2103103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 19, BNS -- Latvian transport must 
integrate into the European transport network, after joint 
transport policy is worked out among Latvia, Lithuania and 
Estonia, Communications Ministry Strategic Planning Department 
director, Aleksandrs Konosevics, told at a press conference. 
  The European Union (EU) plans to form a united system of 
transportation by year 2000 involving also the East European 
states in it. The present EU transport policy is based on 
market economy and free competition, drawing in private capital. 
  Latvian Communications Ministry has to draft a program on 
Latvia's transport system integration into European transport 
network. It must be done by 3rd European conference of 
communications ministers, taking place after two years. 
  Konosevics explained the ministry's specialists will take 
into account EU standards and experience when working out 
Latvian transport policy. EU pays much attention to traffic 
precaution measures and ecology. Besides, the European states 
do not subsidize public transport. 

</TEXT>

