<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Perry's Comments, Visit to `Classified Site' Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2103102194 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 0900 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2103102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry arrived in 
Kiev yesterday on a two-day official visit. I have three tasks 
to fulfill during my visit to Ukraine, stated U.S. Defense 
Secretary William Perry at Borispol airport. The first task is 
to strengthen and renew relations with our old friends; second, 
is to continue working with the Ukrainian Government and the 
Defense Ministry to step up the implementation of the very 
important trilateral Ukrainian-Russian-U.S. agreement signed by 
Presidents Leonid Kravchuk, Boris Yeltsin, and Bill Clinton in 
Moscow in January of this year; and my third task will be to 
cooperate with the Ukrainian Government within the framework of 
the program of economic development and conversion of military 
industrial enterprises. 
  The U.S. delegation is planning to visit Pervomaysk and 
acquaint itself with how a variety of programs on dismantling 
nuclear weapons according to the Moscow trilateral agreement are 
being implemented. After that, Secretary Perry will visit a 
classified site in Dnepropetrovsk, the biggest production 
complex specializing in missile equipment production. For the 
first time in the history of such enterprises, the Pentagon 
chief later emphasized, a U.S. secretary of defense will have 
the opportunity to personally observe operations at one of these 
sites. 

</TEXT>

