<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Majlis Chairman: Meshkov Not President for Crimean Tatars </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003104494 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 0830 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2003104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sevastopol, 19 Mar -- Mustafa Dzhamilev, chairman of 
the Majlis of the Crimean-Tatar people granted an interview to 
the newspaper FLOT UKRAYINYY [FLEET OF UKRAINE]. He said in 
particular, that "Yuriy Meshkov is not a president today for the 
Crimean Tatar people," because his program envisages a revision 
of the existing borders. The chairman of the Majlis said that 
"of all the states of the former union, Ukraine is the only 
country today that renders the most effective assistance to us. 
We are well aware of how complicated the current economic 
situation in the country is and therefore we are not putting 
forward any particular claims." 
  Replying to the question: "Is Russia extending any help to 
you," Dzhamilev said: "We do not receive any practical 
assistance from Russia, however, we should not forget that in 
the years when our people were subject to deportation, Crimea 
was under the jurisdiction of the Russian Federation, and we 
hope to intensify all-around methods of influencing Moscow, 
which bears the bulk of responsibility for the genocide of the 
Crimean Tatars. We will strive to achieve that Moscow finance 
the process of the repatriation, rehabilitation [of the Crimean 
Tatars], and compensation for the losses inflicted on our 
people." 
  Replying to the questions "how does he assess the statement 
by President Yuriy Meshkov to the effect that Ukraine should 
pull its troops out of the territory of the peninsula, and does 
the Black Sea Fleet ensure Crimea's security," Dzhamilev said: 
"This is an irresponsible and provocative statement... the 
Black Sea Fleet issue should be solved quicker and the 
stationing of the foreign state's ships near our shores is one 
of the elements that destabilizes the political situation in 
Crimea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

