<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Nixon Meeting With Kravchuk </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1803152794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 18 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1803152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UNIAN's Mariya Starozhitskaya: "Nixon Called </F>
Kravchuk One of the World's Best Strategists"] 
  [Text] Kiev -- After being in Kiev for four hours ex-U.S. 
President Richard Nixon said of President Leonid Kravchuk: "I 
have always said, and I repeat, that he is one of the world's 
best strategists, who accords with Ukraine's interests and 
understands problems on a global scale." 
  "I spent approximately a week in Russia -- everyone knows 
that after the elections, its position with regard to Ukraine 
and other neighbors became more tough and aggressive," Nixon 
said. "I do not mean that the majority of the leaders in Russia 
now support the position of Zhirinovskiy and others, but in the 
future, there could certainly be precedents when the [United] 
States will have to choose whether to look to Russia or Ukraine. 
  ``Here I will express my personal opinion: Both the United 
States and the Ukrainian people must be interested in Russia's 
economic and political progress. If economic conditions improve 
in Russia, this will mean a worsening of the positions of 
extremist forces such as Zhirinovskiy, who pursues an aggressive 
policy toward Ukraine. Russia is a great state, but it is not 
in its best interest to bite off more than it can chew: It has 
quite enough domestic problems, and I consider economic 
imperialism just as unacceptable as military imperialism." 
  Leonid Kravchuk pointed out that Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov has twice violated Ukrainian legislation with his edict 
on holding a referendum. 
  "It is not a normal democratic and peaceful process to start 
one's activity by violating the law and the constitution," 
Kravchuk said. "If President Meshkov resorts to a 
confrontation, this will be on his conscience." 
  Richard Nixon added that he considers the 19th-century 
Crimean War the most stupid war in history. One such war is 
quite sufficient. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

