<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Says Meshkov `Has Exceeded His Powers' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003204494 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1900 
GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Excerpt" of Interview with Ukrainian President Leonid </F>
Krachuk by unidentified correspondent on 20 March; place not 
given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Announcer] Ukraine President Leonid Kravchuk was 
interviewed today by Ukrainian television. The conversation 
focussed on election issues and relations between central 
executive power bodies and the local executive power in the 
autonomous Republic of Crimea. 
  [Correspondent] Crimea's top executive, President Yuriy 
Meshkov, plans to conduct a poll on 27 March. There has been a 
lot of talk about this poll on the air.... 
  [Kravchuk, interrupting] I talked about it, too. 
  [Correspondent] And about your decree that abolished some of 
its premises. But a lot will depend on, and I quote the U.S. 
embassy press statement, Kiev's considerable self-control. Does 
Kiev have that considerable self-control, Leonid Makarovych? 
  [Kravchuk] Of course it does, because, first of all, this 
self-control needs to be understood in the way that we are 
acting in accordance with the Constitution and the laws of 
Ukraine. It is very important. Whereas the president of Crimea 
has exceeded his powers, that is, has ignored the law, both the 
Ukrainian one and his own, the president of Ukraine is acting 
clearly within the framework of the law. Thus, if you put both 
of these documents [the two presidents' decrees] on the table, 
then you will see that we are acting clearly in accordance with 
the law, while the president of Crimea has violated the norms of 
both Ukraine's and his own law. And that is dangerous. Our 
self-control shows in the fact that we are staying always within 
the law. The Crimean president's lack of self-control in this 
case shows in the fact that he wants to break the law, and he is 
breaking it. I already said this, and I want to say once again 
that the main thing that needs to be done in Crimea today is to 
solve economic problems. 
  [Announcer] That was an excerpt from an interview with 
President of Ukraine Leonid Kravchuk. You can see it in full 
today, at 2200 in the television program "Without Protocol." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16830 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov054_f_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean President Issues Decree on 27 March Poll </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803212394 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1800 GMT 
18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1803212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Crimea's President Yuriy Meshkov issued a decree 
today on organizing and holding a poll among Crimea's citizens 
on 27 March of this year, INTERFAX reported. Yuriy Meshkov 
approved the form for the poll. 
  The document prescribes that Crimea's population will be 
polled on the following issues: 
  -- On their attitude to dual citizenship; 
  -- On the Crimeans' positions regarding the interrelation 
between Kiev and Simferopol on the basis of agreements and 
treaties; and also 
  -- On granting Crimea's president the right to issue 
decrees that have force of law on issues that are not regulated 
by Crimean legislation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

