<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Urges International Conflict Mediation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003182494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1717 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2003182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Armenia wishes the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict to be 
settled through negotiations involving not only Armenia, 
Azerbaijan, Nagorno-Karabakh and Russia but also European 
nations and the United States, an Armenian statesman said. 
  But such talks must be preceded by an unconditional 
ceasefire, Ara Saakian, first deputy chairman of the Armenian 
parliament, told INTERFAX on Sunday. 
  Today both Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan are making 
preliminary conditions, the former pressing for a ceasefire and 
a certain legal status for itself, the latter demanding that 
Nagorno-Karabakh withdraw its troops from Azerbaijani 
territories they occupy, Saakian said. 
  He said Armenia "is building great hopes" on Russia's 
mediation. 
  Meanwhile, disagreements between Armenia and Azerbaijan last 
week prevented the CIS Interparliamentary Assembly meeting in 
St. Petersburg from passing an appeal against the imposition of 
a transport or energy blockade by one Commonwealth state against 
another. Azerbaijani delegation leader Afiyaddin Dzhalilov 
insisted that the appeal include a provision for a mechanism for 
liberating the 20 percent of Azerbaijani lands occupied by 
Nagorno-Karabakh forces and for bringing back home the more than 
a million Azerbaijani refugees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

