<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kokoshin on Perry Talks, Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803171694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1530 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: By diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoi and others] 
  [Text] For the time being it is too early to discuss who 
will go to Brussels and when to sign the NATO program 
Partnership for Peace on behalf of Russia, First Deputy Defense 
Minister of the Russian Federation Andrey Kokoshin told 
reporters on Friday. 
  He said that Mr. Perry's visit to Russia focused on 
bilateral 
relations in the military/political sphere. In particular, the 
two sides discussed the implementation of the air-defense 
treaty, ban on nuclear testing and non-proliferation of nuclear 
arms. 
  "Russia and the U.S. are particularly responsible for 
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, because they are two major 
nuclear powers. We should not focus all of our attention on the 
NATO program Partnership for Peace. It is just "an element" of 
relations between Russia and the West. Partnership For Peace 
should be understood in a broad sense," Kokoshin said. 
  In his opinion, "one should approach Russia's entry in this 
program very seriously." "The interests of Russia and its allies 
under the CIS treaty on collective security should be fully 
taken into account," Kokoshin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

