<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin: Bosnian Agreements Only `First Steps' to Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1903161794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0010 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1903161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Pavel Vanichkin and Vitaliy </F>
Chukseyev] 
  [Text] Washington, 19 Mar -- Vitaliy Churkin, Russian 
Deputy Foreign Minister and the Russian president's special 
envoy, has described the agreements concluded here on the 
formation of a Muslim-Croat Bosnian federation as important, but 
only the very first steps in a peaceful settlement of the 
Bosnian conflict. He attended Friday's White House ceremony at 
which the documents were signed. Alija Izetbegovic, president 
of the Presidency of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bosnian 
Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic, Croatian President Franjo 
Tudjman, and Kresimir Zubak, a representative of the Bosnian 
Croats, appended their signatures to the documents. 
  On the same day Churkin arranged a news conference, at which 
he declared that the agreement on a new Muslim-Croat state 
formation, and especially the agreement on arranging 
confederative ties between it and Croatia were of an interim 
nature. It was a vital condition for a true settlement in 
Bosnia that it preserved its territorial integrity and that the 
Bosnian Serbs, therefore, took part in the peace process, the 
high-ranking Russian diplomat explained. 
  Answering a question from an ITAR-TASS correspondent about 
whether the agreement on confederative relations between the new 
federation and Croatia might be an obstacle to the inclusion of 
the Serbs within the federation, Churkin said: I don't think 
so, since the agreement on a confederation with Croatia is of an 
interim nature. Equally interim is the agreement on the 
formation of the actual federation. In other words, both 
documents may be changed if the Bosnian Serbs decide to become 
involved in implementing them. I am sure that the Serbs will 
demand some changes that will be in keeping with their views on 
the future Bosnia. The Russian deputy foreign minister pointed 
out that the territorial contradictions constituted one of the 
main issues dividing the opposing sides today. 
  Churkin stressed the major role that is currently being 
played in the process of settling the Bosnian conflict by 
American and Russian diplomacy. He noted that the two 
countries' interests in this respect were not opposed in 
principle. He said that evidence of this was provided by the 
praise for Russia's efforts that was expressed at the signing 
ceremony by U.S. President Bill Clinton. Equally high praise for 
Moscow's policy was forthcoming at the meeting that took place 
on the same day with Secretary of State Warren Christopher. 
  During the visit by the Russian president's special envoy to 
the American capital, he also had a conversation with German 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel. He held consultations with 
Charles Redman, the American special envoy on Yugoslavia, and 
met David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, the co-chairmen of the 
peace process in the former Yugoslavia. 
  Churkin told an ITAR-TASS correspondent that Russian 
diplomacy would continue to play an active part in settling the 
Bosnian conflict. He announced that he was flying on 19 March 
to Zagreb to have further talks and to organize a meeting 
between the sides, which are planned for the Russian Embassy on 
25 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16848 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov054_a_94006" </HT>


