<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin on Clinton, Gore Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003225294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1732 
GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003225294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Naryshkin] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb, 20 Mar -- "The U.S. leadership has confirmed 
at the highest level its preparedness to cooperate with Russia 
in the settlement of the crisis in former Yugoslavia," Vitaliy 
Churkin, special envoy of the Russian president, said upon 
arrival in the Croatian capital from Washington on Sunday. 
  "I had talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton, U.S. 
Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher, and Vice President Albert Gore. 
During the talks with Christopher we discussed the main 
directions of our joint work and agreed that the United States 
and Russia will work with all sides involved in the conflict," 
Churkin said in an interview with ITAR-TASS. 
  "In Washington, we discussed the most likely date for a 
meeting between all Bosnian sides. I believe that this meeting 
could be held as early as next week," Churkin said. 
  "Everyone supports our initiative in holding this meeting 
and 
hopes that the signing of the cease-fire agreement will be 
followed by further productive steps. But now what is mainly 
being said is that it is necessary to nudge the sides to the 
conclusion of this agreement to conclude the months of talks. 
Stressing as I do the strengthening of our cooperation with the 
United States, I also invited the U.S. ambassador in Croatia to 
take part in the Zagreb meeting," Churkin said. 
  Vladimir Ivanovskiy, head of the Russian Federation Foreign 
Ministry department for the countries of former Yugoslavia, who 
is in Zagreb, commenting on Russia's approach to the 
Croatian-Serbian settlement process, told the ITAR-TASS 
correspondent today that the Croat leadership's talks with the 
local Serbs should, judging by everything, take place in three 
stages. 
  The first, if circumstances are favorable, could be 
completed 
by 22 March with the signing of a cease-fire agreement and end 
to hostilities. The draft agreement envisages demarcation of 
lines of the Croatian and Serbian forces, withdrawal of heavy 
weapons from a 20-km security zone, and a number of other 
measures. 
  After this talks could begin on restoration of economic and 
transport links with the territories under Serbian control. 
  Political questions including the status of the Serb 
Krajinas 
should, as the most difficult aspect, be left to the third stage 
of a settlement, the Russian diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16849 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov054_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

