<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Draft Agreement Ready </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103162694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1402 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Andrey Naryshkin, ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb, 21 Mar -- Participants in the talks between 
government delegations of Croatia and the Serb Republic of 
Krajina due to open at the Russian Embassy in Zagreb on Tuesday 
will strive toward an agreement on stopping hostilities 
immediately. 
  The talks, which are to be resumed, as is known, at the 
initiative of the Russian side, will be based on a draft 
agreement on a cease-fire drawn up by specialists from UN 
peace-making forces. The Croat delegation is expected to be led 
by Hrvoje Sarinic, head of the republic's security service, and 
the Serb delegation by Rear Admiral Dusan Rakic, defense 
minister of the Serb Republic of Krajina which Croatia does not 
recognize. Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of the Russian 
president, the Russian and U.S. ambassadors in Croatia as well 
as officials from UN peace-making forces and the international 
conference on former Yugoslavia are to attend the talks as 
mediators. 
  The ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned from trustworthy 
sources in Zagreb that the basic content of the draft agreement 
boils down to the following: 
  - The sides agree to cease armed operations forthwith and 
also to cease fire on all lines of contact as of a date to be 
agreed; 
  - The tactical deployment of the armed forces which are 
situated along the line of contact and within a radius of 10 km 
in all directions relative to the line of contact will be frozen 
on the day the agreement is signed and movement of military 
units and sub-units will be banned; 
  - All targetable weapons will be deployed outside the 
region of the line of contact: mortars and antiaircraft guns at 
least 10 km and artillery and tanks at least 20 km; 
  - All sub-units to be withdrawn from the line of contact 
by at least 1,000 meters; 
  - Observance of the cease-fire is to be monitored by the 
UNPROFOR and the EC observer mission; 
  - Joint commissions are being set up at all levels and 
their main task is to mark the terrain where the sides' 
disengagement lines are situated and to investigate any 
cease-fire violations; 
  - A certain number of checkpoints will be opened along the 
entire line of contact. Conditions for the joint commissions to 
meet at the checkpoints will be created. 
  A separate point treats the need for the sides to meet to 
discuss the conditions for the reduction of the armed forces 
within the 10 km security zone. 
  On the eve of the talks Vitaliy Churkin is holding intensive 
consultations in Zagreb with the highest UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Force] officials and with representatives of the international 
conference on the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

