<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Foreign Minister Hata Arrives in Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003212894 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003212894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent F. Tavrovskiy; from the </F>
"Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] Tsutomu Hata, the Japanese foreign minister and 
deputy prime minister, has arrived in Moscow on a three-day 
visit. During meetings with the head of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry and other leaders, Hata is going to discuss a wide 
range of issues. Firstly, long-standing disputes over the Kuril 
Islands, which cause great anxiety on the part of the Japanese 
side in light of the recent statement by Prime Minister 
Chernomyrdin, that there is no territorial problem between our 
two countries. Hata also wants to discuss Russia' policy in the 
former Yugoslavia in greater detail, economic cooperation 
issues, and the possibility of Russia joining G7 -- the minister 
is very reserved regarding the latter. 
  Before departure, Hata admitted frankly that he was going to 
ask Russia's assistance in settling the situation on the Korean 
Peninsula. To all appearances, Marshall Kim Il-song continues 
to develop nuclear weapons, and the pressure exerted by South 
Korea and the United States is evidently insufficient. All 
these issues will be discussed tomorrow when the six-hour time 
lag between Moscow and Tokyo will not be affecting the minister 
so strongly. Today, Hata laid a wreath at the Grave of the 
Unknown soldier and visited the Moscow State University and the 
Morozov hospital. [video shows a press conference, aerial 
pictures of islands, facilities, Hata laying a wreath] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

