<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Criticizes DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2003131094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1247 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2003131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 20 KYODO -- Japanese Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata criticized North Korea on Sunday over its suspected 
nuclear arms development plan, saying Pyongyang is taking a 
stubborn attitude. 
  Hata, speaking to reporters in Moscow, said North Korea's 
tough attitude led to the breakdown of the eighth round of 
working-level inter-Korean talks Saturday. 
  "It is regrettable that the (dialogue) broke down because of 
North Korea's stubborn attitude," he said. 
  The foreign minister, who is on a four-day visit to Russia 
starting Saturday, urged North Korea to respond to serious 
concern among the international community about its nuclear 
development program. He also asked Pyongyang to hold sincere 
talks with South Korea. 
  On Saturday, delegates of North and South Korea met in the 
truce village of Panmunjom for 55 minutes to discuss procedures 
for an inter-Korean exchange of special envoys between Seoul and 
Pyongyang. But the session produced little progress, failing 
even to set a date for the next round. The talks collapsed with 
North Korean negotiators walking away from the dialogue table, 
south officials said. 

</TEXT>

