<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Non-Proliferation Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103131894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1232 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Aleksandr Kopnov, Anatoliy </F>
Krasnov, and Vladimir Solntsev] 
  [Text] Moscow, 21 March -- Strengthening and maintaining 
the regime of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, including 
IAEA [International Atomic Energy Agency] inspections, is a 
fundamental issue for Russia, Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev stated today after talks with Tsutomu Hata, Japanese 
deputy prime minister and foreign minister. 
  Answering questions from journalists about whether there was 
discussion at their meeting of the problems regarding steps 
Moscow might take in regard to Pyongyang, which is suspected of 
developing nuclear weapons, the Russian minister said: "We 
shall firmly insist upon fulfilment of all necessary obligations 
and procedures." The forms in which this issue might be 
settled, he pointed out, are now being discussed at bilateral 
negotiations and the relevant consultations are under way, 
including through IAEA channels. "I think we shall be acting 
with Japan very closely, as well as with other partners," Andrey 
Kozyrev stressed. 

</TEXT>

