<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shared Concern Over DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103181194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1750 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 21 TASS -- Russia and Japan are of the 
same opinion about the current "alarming situation" around the 
North Korean nuclear problem which may become still more 
serious, Aleksandr Panov, deputy foreign minister of the Russian 
Federation, told ITAR-TASS in an exclusive interview after the 
talks between Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and 
Tsutomu Hata, deputy premier and foreign minister of Japan, in 
Moscow today. 
  According to Aleksandr Panov, Moscow and Tokyo stand for 
strengthening of the regime of nuclear non-proliferation and for 
the Korean Peninsular becoming a nuclear-free zone. Both sides, 
he noted, consider it necessary to maintain a constant mutual 
contact, continue negotiations on the nuclear problem of North 
Korea, and probably look for some other approaches as the 
present ones proved to be insufficiently effective. 
  Asked about what joint contribution Moscow and Tokyo could 
make to the ensuring of security in the Far East and in the 
Asian-Pacific region as a whole, the Russian senior diplomat 
said both sides had earlier expressed the coincidence of views 
on this problem. 
  Russia and Japan consider it important, while maintaining 
the 
existing treaties and agreements, to move towards cooperation on 
a subregional level. The Russian Foreign Ministry believes that 
such a subregional mechanism could be created in particular in 
the basin of the Sea of Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

