<H3> <TI>   Reportage of Iranian Plane Crash in Karabakh </TI></H3>
<H4>   Karabakh Hints Azeris Responsible </H4>
<F P=102> LD1903140494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1202 
GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1903140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By unidentified ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 19 Mar -- Representatives of the Islamic 
Republic of Iran have started work at the site of the crash of 
the Iranian C-130 Hercules military transport plane. 
  The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Nagorno-Karabakh 
Republic told an ITAR-TASS correspondent by telephone today that 
the republic's authorities had expressed condolences to the 
families of those who died and to the Iranian people. A state 
commission to investigate the cause of the air crash has been 
set up. 
  According to reports from other Karabakh sources, local 
experts do not rule out the possibility that the Iranian plane 
could have been shot down by the Azerbaijani side. In their 
opinion, information about the radio intercept, which the 
Karabakh side bears witness to, as does the fact that at the 
site where the military plane came down near the village of 
Noragyukh in Askerasnkiy [Askeran] Rayon, there are fragments of 
five surface-to-air class missiles launched over the past 18 
months from anti-aircraft missile systems in the Azerbaijani 
towns of Mingechaur and TerTer. 
  However, Stepanakert is refraining from making any official 
statements until the commission has given its findings. One 
possible motive is said to be that the cause of the crash of the 
military helicopter carrying several Azerbaijani leaders in 
November 1991 in Nagorno-Karabakh has still not been 
established. The Azerbaijani side placed the blame on 
Stepanakert then without any proof, but the matter has still not 
been cleared up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

