<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage of Iranian Plane Crash in Karabakh </TI></H3>
<H4>   Iranian Experts: Rocket `Likely' Cause </H4>
<F P=102> LD2003113394 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1030 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The investigation by a group of Iranian experts into 
the cause of the crash in Khankendi [Stepanakert] of a C-130 
aircraft belonging to the Islamic Republic of Iran is continuing 
at the crash site. Although the primary cause of the plane 
crash is not definitely clear yet and the state authorities are 
waiting for the investigation results from the dispatched group, 
agency reports and statements by local authorities indicate that 
it is likely that the plane crashed after being hit by a rocket. 
  According to a Central News Unit report, official Azeri 
authorities say that the Iranian C-130 was downed by Armenian 
anti-aircraft artillery positioned in the Khankendi area, which 
is a disputed area in Karabakh. Nevertheless, those reports 
have been rejected by Armenian authorities. 
  Our correspondent has been informed by an aviation expert 
that the Iranian captain had established contact with the 
Yerevan airport, but the contact was unsuccessful. The captain 
had also made contact with a Russian aircraft flying in the 
vicinity in order to coordinate with the airport with his 
assistance. The aviation experts believe it is unlikely that 
the C-130 plane crashed as a result of a technical fault. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

