<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage of Iranian Plane Crash in Karabakh </TI></H3>
<H4>   Victims' Bodies To Be Flown Home </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103092194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0900 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tigran Liloyan] </F>

    [Text] Yerevan March 21 TASS -- 34 bodies of people killed 
in 
the crash of the Iranian C-130 plane in Nagorno-Karabakh, 
including nine children, will be sent home on Monday in presence 
of Iranian diplomats, relatives and experts who arrived in 
Yerevan. 
  The Iranian experts intend to fly to Stepanakert to 
participate in the investigation of the aircrash on the spot. 
  It became known from reliable sources that the recording of 
the talk between traffic controllers of the Yerevan airport and 
the crew of the Iranian plane was sealed and would be studied by 
experts. 
  The C-130 plane had to fly through the Armenian airspace 
bound for Tehran, but deviated 100 kilometres from the route for 
unknown reasons. 
  It thus got into the airspace of Azerbaijan and crashed 
three 
kilometres off Stepanakert, the capital of Nagorno-Karabakh. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

