Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage of Iranian Plane Crash in Karabakh </TI></H3>
<H4>   Russian Experts on Planes's Mission </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103095494 Mosow ITAR-TASS in English 0927 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mosow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS corespondent Anatoliy Yurin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 21 TASS -- Russian military experts do 
not rule out a possibility that the Iranian C-130 plane which 
crashed near Stepanakert on Friday was on a reconnaisance 
mission in Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  "Why did Iranian pilots who knew that medium altitudes over 
a 
combat zone (of Nagorno-Karabakh) are mortally dangerous still 
flew towards Stepanakert and further headed towards the 
strategically important Lachin corridor (connecting the enclave 
with Armenia)", the experts told TASS on Monday. 
  They added that neither the special commission investigating 
the crash, nor the simultaneous statements of Armenians and 
Azeris denying their involvement in the crash will give an 
answer to the main question -- why the C-130 appeared in the 
airspace of Nagorno-Karabakh and why did the crew choose the 
course right over the combat area?. 
  The experts stressed that the crew of the plane had an 
unusually big number of members and that the craft did not need 
any emergency landing even if the cockpit was depressurised. 
  The plane could have landed in Gyandzha or Shamkhor in 
Azerbaijan where runways of former Soviet military airfields are 
big enough for all types of heavy planes. 
  The experts do not rule out that one of the warring sides 
shot down the plane mistaking it for an enemy one. It is quite 
possible the transport craft was attacked from a mobile 
anti-aircraft missile which are in big numbers in the combat 
zone, they added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

