<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Approves Removal of Vladivostok Mayor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803161494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1445 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The deputy chief of the regional desk of President 
Yeltsin's Office Sergey Samoylov has told an IF reporter the 
president's men approved the removal of Vladivostok's Mayor 
Viktor Cherepkov from office. 
  Cherepkov was unseated Wednesday evening. Addressing the 
present situation in Vladivostok, Samoylov said he had kept an 
eye on Cherepkov's performance ever since he rose to power. 
  Soon after he was elected Mayor, Cherepkov arrived in Moscow 
with a bulky package of documents detrimental to the image of 
Governor Yevgeniy Nazdratenko of the Primorskiy Region. A 
subsequent inquiry showed, however, that the negative data 
related mostly to performance by Nazdratenko's predecessor 
Kuznetsov. 
  Cherepkov's opponents responded in kind and presented Moscow 
with a package of negative data on his performance. They 
claimed, among other things, that, pretending to be a sea 
captain, Cherepkov had visited Japan to buy a dozen cars. 
  According to Samoylov, Cherepkov spent at least four of his 
several months in office in Moscow. His dispute with the 
region's leaders diverted his attention from the city's 
problems. More than once he moved to restructure the city 
government, took control of the districts' budgets and earmarked 
substantial sums in aid to the local media editions which acted 
as his mouthpiece. His efforts to update the city government 
proved a failure. 
  The State Legal Administration suggested that Governor 
Yevgeniy Nazdratenko unseat Cherepkov. First, however, 
Nazdratenko was to have appeared on television to explain what 
motivated his move against the Vladivostok Mayor. The 
Primorskiy Administration preferred to stall until Viktor 
Cherepkov was accused of bribe-taking and a number of his 
associates were arrested, several weeks ago. On representation 
from the court authorities, Cherepkov was finally removed from 
office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16887 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov054_d_94001" </HT>


