<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage of Iranian Plane Crash in Karabakh </TI></H3>
<H4>   Armenian Official's Statement </H4>
<F P=102> LD1803210194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1904 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803210194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tigran Liloyan] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan March 18 TASS -- Although Armenia has 
nothing to do with Thursday's crash of the Iranian aircraft 
outside its skies, it renders comprehensive assistance to the 
Iranian authorities in the crash investigation, First Deputy 
Armenian Foreign Minister Zhirair Liparityan told a briefing for 
correspondents and representatives of foreign embassies tonight. 
  In his words, "the Iranian C-130 plane on its way from 
Moscow 
to Tehran passed Georgia at 22:08 on March 17 but did not enter 
the Armenian skies as it was planned. The aircraft deviated 
from the air corridor by approximately 100 kilometers, entered 
the Azeri skies and headed for Nagorno-Karabakh." 
  According to information of the Armenian Foreign Ministry, 
"the plane crashed approximately 14 kilometers away from 
Stepanakert, meanwhile the Karabakh Information and Press 
Department reports the accident place five kilometers away from 
the Karabakh capital". All the passengers and 14 crew members 
died. 
  "The plane carried 31 people," said Liparityan. He made no 
further comments, saying he "does not have more information". 
  A statement of the Armenian Government's Civil Aviation 
Department was circulated tonight to say "the Iranian plane on 
its way from Moscow to Tehran deviated from its route by 100 
kilometers on unknown reasons at 22:30 on March 17 and found 
itself in the Karabakh skies. The plane crashed five kilometers 
away from Stepanakert. Circumstances of the crash are being 
specified". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

