<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 22 March </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203070794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0644 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, March 22 (TASS) -- Russian newspapers 
highlight the meeting between Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
and Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, and elections to the 
local power bodies. 
  ROSSIISKIYE VESTI quotes Chernomyrdin as saying about the 
results of the talks with Mr Hata that "Russia, when tackling a 
solution to the territorial dispute with Japan, will act without 
haste. The issue cannot be resolved at a sweep". The newspaper 
points out that the Russian premier expressed hope that the 
issue would be resolved. "We shall approach the conclusion of a 
peace treaty between our two countries in any case. A solution 
to the territorial problem is one of prerequisites for such a 
treaty". 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA remarks in this connection that "it is, 
probably, the Russian side that to a greater extent remains 
pleased with the results of the talks held in Moscow by Japanese 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata. Although the meeting with 
Russian premier gave certain satisfaction to the Japanese 
minister: This time the Russian premier did not make tough 
remarks, as he did at the end of last year, about it being 
impossible to hand over the Kuril Islands under any 
circumstances". 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA on elections to local power bodies: 
  "Last Sunday's elections to the local representative power 
bodies in the regions of the Russian Federation revealed, on the 
whole, the electorate's indifference and passivity. 
Irrespective of the final election results, this conclusion 
could be drawn immediately after the polls closed." 
  TRUD on local election results: 
  "Such outcome of the elections in a number of Russian 
regions 
can hardly satisfy the federal authorities either. For a low 
turnout of voters is indicative of the Russians' low trust in 
power in general. And this is understandable. Over the past 
several years, there were so many well wishers who promised 
people a lot. Meanwhile, the life of the majority of ordinary 
citizens has not changed for the better". 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA (RED STAR) on local election results: 
  "People, having got disillusioned with the abilities of `the 
people's elected representatives' to change if only anything in 
their life, were not in a hurry to go to the polls. 
  "Experts explain the passiveness of the population by a 
number of other reasons as well. Not of least importance in 
this respect is the excessively protracted nature of the 
election campaign, and Moscow's insufficient interest in the 
electoral process at the local level". 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA carries an interview with Colonel-General 
Georgiy Kondratyev, Russian deputy minister of defence, under 
the headline " The Second Phase of the Reform: What Awaits the 
Army". 
  The newspaper points out that the first phase of the 
reforming of the Russian Army and Navy is over. Main organising 
measures to create the armed forces of Russia proper have been 
carried out. 
  In response to a question what awaits the armed forces in 
the 
future, the deputy defence minister said: "The armed forces will 
become, firstly, a relatively small but powerful and modile army 
provided with the most effective systems of weapons and military 
hardware and capable of defending Russia from encroachments from 
the outside and be the guarantor of peace and stability in the 
country. 
  "Secondly, this will be an army of a democratic state, which 
has fundamentally different relationships with society and the 
state and enjoying respect and prestige among the people. 
  "Thirdly, this will be an important instrument of national 
policy, maintaining all the best from the traditions of its 
predecessors, everything that was connected with the 
accomplishment of exclusively defensive tasks. 
  "These three positions in point of fact reflect the 
principal 
meaning of the current process of the Russian Armed Forces 
reform", General Kondratyev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

