<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saakyan Calls for Cease-Fire Prior to Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103165094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1537 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: by Nikolay </F>
Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovsky] 
  [Text] Armenia favors a peaceful solution to the regional 
conflict through peace talks involving Azerbaijan, 
Nagorno-Karabakh, Armenia and Russia as well as European 
countries and the U.S., Deputy Speaker of Parliament Ara Saakyan 
told Interfax. However, he said that unconditional cease-fire 
should precede any such talks. 
  Saakyan said that unlike Azerbaijan which insists on the 
withdrawal of Armenian forces from occupied Azeri lands as a 
condition for cease-fire, Nagorno-Karabakh demands an end to the 
fighting and definition of its status first. 
  In his words, Yerevan is laying great hopes on Russia's 
peace 
effort in the region. 
  In the meantime, the continued differences between Yerevan 
and Baku had prevented the CIS interparliamentary assembly 
meeting in St. Petersburg over the weekend from adopting an 
appeal on CIS states not to resort to transport or energy 
blockade against each other. 
  Leader of the Azeri parliamentary delegation Afiyaddin 
Jalilov spoke of 20 percent of Azeri territory being annexed by 
Karabakh Armenians calling to include into the final paper a 
provision for Armenian pullout and the return of more than a 
million Azeri refugees to their homes. 

</TEXT>

