<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Zlenko Visits Poland </TI></H3>
<H4>   Wants `Equal Cooperation' With West </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103193094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1711 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Nekrasova] </F>
  [Text] Lvov March 21 TASS -- Ukraine does not want to be a 
buffer between the East and West. It wants to be an equal 
partner, Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko told a news 
conference in Lvov, western Ukraine, on Monday. 
  The minister made a stopover in Lvov on his way from the 
Czech Republic to Poland where he will discuss the Partnership 
for Peace Programme. 
  Zlenko pointed out that Ukraine is interested in expanding 
regional and sub-regional cooperation, particularly with the 
Carpathian region, and joining the Visegrad group which unites 
Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia and Hungary. 
  The minister said that the opinion that Ukraine is not 
welcome in Europe is wrong, adding that after Poland he will fly 
to Brussels to sign an agreement on cooperation with the 
European Union. "Ukraine can and will cooperate with Western 
states. It has a potential for equal cooperation. There is 
also a reciprocal interest among the European powers," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16906 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov055_e_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Zlenko Visits Poland </TI></H3>
<H4>   Signs `Partnership' Agreements </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103224094 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 2015 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103224094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 21 Mar -- UNIAN has reported that Ukrainian 
Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko on 21 March began his visit to 
the Republic of Poland. On the same day he had a tete-a-tete 
conversation with Polish Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski. 
According to some information, they discussed the two sides' 
views on the Partnership for Peace program joined by the two 
states. After this, the foreign ministers signed a declaration 
on the principles of forming Ukrainian-Polish partnership and an 
agreement on protecting the graves and places in memory of 
victims of war and reprisals. 
  Commenting on the results of the Ukrainian-Polish 
negotiations and the agreement signed, Ukrainian Ambassador to 
Poland Hennadiy Udovenko stated to a UNIAN correspondent that 
the documents signed did not signify a union between Ukraine and 
Poland. They did, however, make the declaration of strategic 
partnership more specific. The ambassador's view is that 
"Ukrainian-Polish relations are at a stage of stagnation and are 
in need of a fresh impetus," in view of which he categorically 
opposed the opinion of some of the Polish mass media that the 
minister's visit was inexpedient ahead of the elections to 
Ukraine's parliament. He considers the visit very topical 
indeed. 
  Answering the UNIAN correspondent's question on whether the 
issue of Ukraine possibly joining the France-Germany-Poland 
geopolitical axis was discussed at the meeting, the ambassador 
stated Ukraine was interested in this issue but Poland had not 
decided yet. 

</TEXT>

