<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin Denies Plot </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203130294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1242 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 22 TASS -- Yet another "top Russian 
official", who was said to be involved in an alleged coup 
planned to oust Boris Yeltsin, denied the accusations calling 
them a "clumsy political joke". 
  "I laughed when I saw my name among the (coup) plotters", 
Mikhail Poltoranin, a former aide of the president and currently 
the chairman of the State Duma commission on information policy, 
told TASS on Tuesday. 
  The OBSHCHAYA GAZETA said last week Poltorainin and several 
other top officials were involved in plotting to oust the 
president. The office of the Russian prosecutor general said it 
was checking whether the report corresponds to reality and 
threatened to bring criminal charges against the newspaper if 
the information turned out to be false. 
  Poltoranin said that the report was "especially silly", all 
names listed there were politically incompatible and plans 
unrealistic. He said he was confused by the fact that the 
Russian press paid so much attention to the report. "Only 
limited and incompetent people can get on such a bait", he 
stressed. 
  On Monday another "plotter" denied his involvement in the 
"coup". First Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets asked the 
prosecutor's office to clear up the accusations against him. 
Moscow Mayor Yuriy Luzhkov was also on the list. He was the 
first to deny the allegations in a Sunday TV interview. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

