<H3> <TI>   Soskovets Not To Respond </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203135994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1338 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 22 TASS -- "First Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets has not officially complained to the 
procurator-general's office against the article `Buds Swelling. 
For a New Putsch?', published in the 11th issue of the 
OBSHCHAYA GAZETA here last Friday," says a statement by the 
first vice-premier's press secretary, forwarded to ITAR-TASS 
today. (The article said that Soskovets was a member of an 
allegedly existing "group of state leaders" wishing to remove 
Boris Yeltsin from power -- ITAR-TASS). 
  "In principle, he has no intention of reacting in any way to 
such publications," the statement says. 
  "At the same time, I must express concern on behalf of the 
first vice-premier in connection with attempts to split our 
society asunder, to sow discord within the state-governing 
structures, among prominent politicians and public leaders. 
Such attempts directly contradict the tendency towards concord, 
gaining strength in our society, which was created by President 
Yeltsin's recent initiatives," the document stresses. 
  "Oleg Soskovets believes that the consolidation of civil 
peace will be promoted also by the government-planned measures 
to stabilise the economy and increase the social character of 
the ongoing reforms," the press secretary says in his official 
document. "The way to consolidate and develop Russia lies 
through the cooperation of all the organs of power, all the 
political parties, public movements and social groups. The 
first vice-premier, just as other members of the government, 
regards our president as the guarantor of peace, tranquility and 
stability in the country." 

</TEXT>

