<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Cites Apprehensions on 1991 Coup Case </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2103110594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 18 Mar 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PM2103110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina report specially </F>
for ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA: "Three Options in Quest for Truth. 
Which One Will Supreme Court Choose?"] 
  [Text] The investigation into the State Committee for the 
State of Emergency [SCSE] case is the way to establish the 
historical truth, Yuriy Baturin, an aide to the Russian 
president, believes. 
  "If the renewed judicial investigation into the SCSE case is 
brought to an end once again, it will have major moral 
repercussions for society. Society will be led away from the 
quest for the historical truth." This position was voiced in an 
interview with this ITAR-TASS correspondent by Yuriy Baturin, 
the Russian president's national security aide. And he 
particularly emphasized in the conversation that his opinion 
should in no way be interpreted as pressuring the Supreme Court. 
  Baturin's fears in connection with the emergence of new 
"blank spots" in the country's history are based on the fact 
that in the prevailing situation -- whereby the SCSE members 
have been granted an amnesty in violation of Article 5 of the 
Code of Criminal Procedure, following which this decision was 
repealed by the Military Collegium -- at the stage of the 
scheduled new judicial investigation, three options are 
possible: either the search for the truth is continued until a 
conviction or acquittal is gained, after which the amnesty would 
come into force; or the case is sent for additional 
investigation; or the case is closed. 
  "If the Supreme Court takes the first option it will trigger 
a new judicial investigation. This would mean restoring 
legality and continuing the search for the truth. Then we could 
take our hat off to the Supreme Court," Yuriy Baturin said. 
  The second option -- of sending the case back for additional 
investigation -- would mean that the prosecutor's office would 
again study 150 bulky volumes of evidence. 
  The third option would be to close the case at the new stage 
in light of the legitimate ground of the act of amnesty. "This 
may be a well-conceived way of legitimately closing the case 
illegally," was how Baturin put it, since, although it was 
illegal to close the case in the course of the judicial 
investigation, the law does not prevent this now that a new 
investigation is in preparation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16929 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov055_b_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Chief Briefs Duma on Arms, U.S. Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103185294 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1605 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer Irina Merkulova] A closed session of the 
lower house's Committee on International Affairs was held at the 
State Duma today. It was attended by Yevgeniy Primakov, 
director of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service [FIS]. In an 
interview with our correspondent, Yuriy Kobaladze, the head of 
the FIS's Press Bureau, described the aim of this meeting in the 
following terms: 
  [Begin Kobaladze recording] This is normal international 
practice. This was simply a way of telling MP's what the 
intelligence service is doing, the tasks it is facing, and the 
way it is tackling them. [end recording] 
  [Merkulova] At the same time, our correspondent learned the 
following: 
  [Begin Correspondent Aleksey Venediktov recording] Moscow 
Echo's sources say that in his address, Primakov referred to 
certain inconsistencies between the Constitution adopted on 12 
December and the law on foreign intelligence. However, arms 
exports were the main topic. Primakov expressed conviction that 
arms sales must be controlled by a single monopoly, 
Rosvooruzheniye, rather than several firms competing among 
themselves. The FIS director said that arms exports could earn 
the country substantial profits -- and not just in Russia's 
traditional markets. 
  He stressed that Russia's intelligence service had observed 
a 
drawing together of the positions of Iran and Turkey, both in 
Afghanistan and the Transcaucasus. 
  Referring to the United States' stance on various questions, 
Primakov noted that according to his information, the United 
States supports Belarus' entry into the ruble zone and advocates 
the preservation of Russia's unity. 
  According to our sources, the hearings on foreign 
intelligence were more reminiscent of a scholarly seminar than a 
chance for MP's to learn about state secrets. However, the 
important thing is that the first contact has been established, 
our sources stressed. [end recording] 
  [Merkulova] Yuriy Kobaladze reacted in the following manner 
when we asked him to confirm or deny that information: 
  [Begin Kobaladze recording] I cannot comment on those 
points. 
If Duma sources supply you with such information, you should 
quote Duma sources. 
  [Merkulova] Let me add that the State Duma's Committee on 
International Affairs also refused to comment. It advised that 
this report should not even be broadcast. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

