<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Finance Minister on Defense Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2203132194 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 22 Mar 94 
First Edition p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2203132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Reserves at 'Zero'"] </F>
  [Text] If all the Defense Ministry's funding requests are 
met, "it would virtually be necessary to stop economic relations 
in the country, switch the state to labor camps, and carry out 
the tasks formulated by the Defense Ministry." This was stated 
by Andrey Vavilov, Russian Federation deputy finance minister. 
  Whereas in 1992-1993 military spending accounted for around 
5 
percent of GDP, this year it will represent 5.03 percent, A. 
Vavilov said. Pointing to the need to cut defense spending in 
the light of Russia's foreign policy commitments, the deputy 
minister admitted that circumstances do not permit this process 
to begin. According to A. Vavilov, the Russian troop withdrawal 
from distant and nearby foreign countries in particular and 
provision for these servicemen will require very considerable 
expenditure. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

