<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Launch Pads, Silos in Amur Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103185894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1719 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia plans to set up new launch pads and silos for 
new generation missiles in the Far Eastern town of Svobodny 
(Amur region) between 1996 and 2000, a spokesman for the 
country's military space forces (MSF) told Interfax. 
  MSF which is responsible for space communications and 
satellite intelligence gathering plans a rebuilding of the first 
of the 60 silos left after the destruction of SS-11 ICBMs for 
launches of a new generation booster developed on the basis of 
an SS-19 missile by 1996. As many as five such silos will be 
rebuilt, said the spokesman. 
  Russia's SS-19 two-stage missiles with a payload of 105.6 
tons each are to be destroyed by the year 2003 as envisaged by 
the START-2 agreement between Moscow and Washington. 
  It is also known that MSF plans an environmentally safe 
general purpose launch pad for a new generation heavy duty 
Angara-24 missile. 
  An MSF official said that since the new booster "can be 
transformed depending on a payload and altitude", the new launch 
pad would operate on the principle of "a changeable circus 
arena". 
  The new booster is to undergo trial tests during 1998-1999 
before being fired into outer space a year or two later. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

