<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cargo Spaceship Launched To Service Mir Station </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203125194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1138 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At 7:54, Moscow time, on Tuesday, a cargo spaceship, 
to be known as Progress-M-22, was launched in line with the 
Russian program of servicing the manned space station Mir. 
Since January 8 Viktor Afanasiyev, Yuriy Usachev and Valeriy 
Polyakov have been working as its 14th crew aboard the Mir. 
  The press service of the Russian Space Force has told 
Interfax that all the systems aboard the Progress are 
functioning as they should. The Space Force was responsoble for 
the preparation and launching of Progress-M-22. 
  A Force spokesman said the cargo ship is to deliver to the 
station additional research equipment, food, oxygen, drinking 
water, medical equipment, fuel and an oxidizer for Mir's engine. 
The Progress' payload amounts to 2.3 tons. 

</TEXT>

