<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission's Preliminary Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103201194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1700 
GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Mar -- An ITAR-TASS correspondent was 
informed at the Central Election Committee that according to 
preliminary results elections to bodies of representative power 
that were held on Sunday are considered valid in 13 of the 17 
parts of the Russian Federation. 
  Viktor Klimov, head of the organization and methods 
department, explained that over two-thirds of the deputy corps 
of the legislative assemblies -- or oblast dumas as the new 
bodies of representative power in the regions are mostly called 
-- had been elected in these regions. That is just the number 
of deputies necessary for the body to be considered capable, for 
it to convene and start working. The rest of its members in the 
regions will be elected in repeated elections, the dates for 
which will be set locally. Viktor Klimov said "the elections 
had given 100 per cent results" only in three parts of the 
federation -- the Aginsk, Buryat, and Komi-Permyak autonomous 
okrugs. In each of the three parts, deputies had been elected 
from all 15 okrugs and their representative bodies were at full 
strength. 
  In three parts of the federation the elections have been 
deemed invalid. In St.Petersburg they have been prolonged to 
today by the decision of the mayor. 

</TEXT>

