<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kiev Protests Donbass Referendum on State Language </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103212094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2002 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Gordeyev] </F>
  [Text] Donetsk March 21 TASS -- It seems that the very word 
"referendum" has begun to irritate Ukrainian authorities after 
two weeks of fruitless disputes between Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk and newly elected Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov about a referendum in the Crimea. 
  The polemics which tends to involve more and more political 
forces has distracted the Ukrainian public from yet another 
plebiscite in the Donbass coal basin scheduled for March 27. 
  Residents of the region were supposed to say whether or not 
the Russian language should be considered as a second state 
language in Ukraine and express their attitude towards Ukraine's 
administrative division and participation in the Commonwealth of 
Independent States. 
  The decision to hold the referendum was adopted by the 
regional council on February 22. However, it had taken Kiev 
authorities a month to respond by ordering the public prosecutor 
to protest the council's decision. The Russian-speaking region 
said it will convene an urgent session of the regional council 
on March 23 to discuss further steps. 
  Meanwhile, the Lugansk region of Ukraine has announced its 
decision to hold a similar poll on the state language. 

</TEXT>

