<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Crimean Pre-Election Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Tatar Officials Criticize Referendum </H4>
<F P=102> MK1803123094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 18 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1803123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric: </F>
"Crimea"] 
  [Text] The Crimean Tatars think that the holding of a 
referendum on 27 March on the peninsula's relationship with 
Ukraine and on the dual citizenship problem contravene both 
Ukraine's laws and those of the Republic of Crimea. This was 
stated on 17 March by Refat Chubarov, deputy chairman of the 
Tatar People's Assembly, in an interview with a NEGA 
correspondent. R. Chubarov personally supports the Ukraine 
president's edict canceling two points in Crimea President Yu. 
Meshkov's edict. In his opinion, "the war of laws unleashed 
between the Republic of Crimea and Ukraine, which will have a 
continuation, will push Crimea into an abyss." In which case 
one would not be able to talk about any economic transformations 
on the peninsula, R. Chubarov thinks. 
  The Crimea president's decision to put his representatives 
in 
charge of city and rayon executive committees is drawing 
negative reactions in the regions. In particular, Sergey 
Kunitsyn, chairman of Krasnyy Perekop town soviet and deputy of 
the Supreme Soviet of Ukraine, described these intentions 
"illegal and contravening the Constitution of the Republic of 
Crimea." Under the Constitution of Crimea, an executive 
committee is an organ of a soviet, and a soviet is formed 
through the holding of general elections, S. Kunitsin thinks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

