<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Meets Major; Agreements Signed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103210294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1938 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Gennadiy Kulagin, Nikolay </F>
Pakhomov and Yuriy Sidorov] 
  [Text] London March 21 TASS -- A meeting between President 
of Kazakhstan Nursultan Nazarbayev, who arrived here on an 
official visit, and British Prime Minister John Major ended 
after signing a number of important bilateral agreements in 
London today. 
  The documents included a joint declaration on friendship and 
mutual understanding, an agreement on cooperation in the spheres 
of education, science and culture, a joint declaration on 
economic cooperation, a convention on avoiding double taxation, 
an agreement on air transport and a declaration on cooperation 
between foreign political departments. 
  In honour of the esteemed guest a guard-of-honour was 
presented and Kazakhstan's national anthem was played in the 
British Foreign Office yard. 
  Summing up the results of the talks, John Major said that 
discussions were held on questions of investment in Kazakhstan's 
economy, and also on steps to increase turnover. The head of 
the British Government noted that the development of cooperation 
in these spheres will help good relations established between 
Great Britain and Kazakhstan. He emphasised that his government 
will explore opportunities for the implementation of the 
understandings already reached. 
  The British prime minister accepted Nursultan Nazarbayev's 
invitation to visit Kazakhstan. He also highly appreciated 
Nazarbayev's initiative to call a conference on steps to 
increase trust and security in Asia. This question was 
comprehensively discussed at the meeting, and the foreign 
ministers of the two countries are continuing consultations on 
this topic, John Major added. 

</TEXT>

