<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Postpones Procedure Approval, Rejects LDP Amendment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803181494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1742 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 18 TASS -- The Russian parliament's 
lower house, the State Duma, again postponed the approval of its 
working procedure until a later date. Speaker Ivan Rybkin told 
lawmakers the committee for organization of the Duma's 
activities discovered during the lunch-break that many of the 
amendments moved by people's deputies before discussing the 
working procedure in the second reading were not taken into 
account. 
  Meanwhile, the first half of today's plenary meeting of the 
State Duma was focused on this issue. Ultranationalist leader 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy of Russia's Liberal Democratic Party [LDP] 
made another attempt to talk lawmakers into approving the 
amendment moved by his party about the so-called "imperative 
mandate". Under this amendment, a deputy quitting a 
parliamentary faction is to be stripped of his credentials and 
replaced by the next member on the party list. To push this 
amendment through parliament, Zhirinovskiy promised to the 
deputies' groups "December 12 Union" and "Russian Path", which 
were denied registration because of insufficient numerical 
strength, that the Liberal Democratic faction would vote for an 
amendment reducing the number of deputies required for 
registration. The Liberal Democrat leader suggested that the 
two amendments be voted as a "package", but lawmakers rejected 
the suggestion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16979 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov055_c_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

