<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reaction to Iranian Plane Crash </TI></H3>
<H4>   Experts: Reconnaissance Mission Theory </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103194094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1924 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yerevan/Moscow March 21 TASS - A group of experts 
from the Iranian air forces and civil aviation agency, headed by 
General Ali Rezvani, arrived on Monday to the site of a crash of 
the Iranian C-130 aircraft which killed 34 people on Friday, 
Armenian Vice-President Gagik Arutyunyan told reporters today. 
  The plane had to fly through the Armenian airspace bound for 
Tehran, but deviated 100 kilometres from the route for unknown 
reasons and hit the ground several miles of [as received] 
Stepanakert, the adminstrative centre of the break-away 
Nagorno-Karabakh province of Azerbaijan. 
  The group of Iranian experts is accompanied by a civil 
aviation official of the Commonwealth of Independent States. 
According to the vice-president, experts are expected to 
complete the investigation and be back in yerevan later in the 
day. 
  The vice president stated that there had been no radio 
communication betwen traffic controllers of the Yerevan airport 
and the crew of the Iranian plane. Both the traffic controllers 
and the crew communicated with a Russian passenger aircraft 
which was on its regular flight in the Armenia's airspace at the 
moment. Records of these conversations are now being studied by 
experts. 
  Meanwhile, Russian military experts do not exclude a 
possibility that the Iranian C-130 plane was on a reconnaissance 
mission in Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  The experts believe that it is most unlikely that the crash 
had been caused by the depressurization of the cockpit. 
  Colonel Aleksey Grekhov, navigator-inspector of the safety 
department of the military transport aviation of the Russian air 
forces, told ITAR-TASS that "there had not been a single case 
when an airplane hit the ground because of depressurization". 
According to the colonel, almost all air trafic in the Afghan 
war had been carried out by depressurized aircraft "but all 
flights were a success unless the planes had been attacked". 
  The experts are cautious about any resolute conclusions 
until 
they get answers to some questions. Why did the crew of the 
plane have an unusually big number of members (13 instead of a 
regular crew of four)? Why did not the plane ask for landing in 
Gyandzha or Shamkhor in Azerbaijan where runways of former 
Soviet military airfields were big enough for all types of heavy 
planes? Why did the plane maintain radio exchange only with a 
Russian aircraft and not with any of the ground services? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

