<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yerevan, MARCH 21 (SNARK)--There may be no black box 
in the Iranian airplane crashed in Karabakh last week. The 
Armenia's Vice-President Gagik Arutyunyan told about that today 
at the press-briefing for reporters. He said that airplanes 
S-130 [as received] don't always have black boxes. 
  Mr. Arutyunyan pointed out that the Iranian special 
commission together with the CIS and Armenia representatives 
flew off to the accident's place in Karabakh. 
  According to clarified data, 34 people died as a result of 
this accident, including women and children. Their remains were 
delivered in Yerevan, and on March 21 they will be conveyed to 
Iran. 
  Mr. Arutyunyan also said that according to data received 
from 
the Iran Embassy to Yerevan, the airplane tried to make an 
emergency landing. It lost height and got from 7500 to 3500 
meters. The Armenian dispatching service tried to get him 
through the Russian airplane flying from Mineralnye Vody [name 
as received] to the Arabian Emirates. However this attempt 
wasn't a success. 

</TEXT>

