<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Japanese Foreign Minister Hata's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kozyrev Proposes Talks on DPRK </H4>
<F P=102> OW2103234294 Tokyo KYODO in English 2302 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2103234294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 21 KYODO -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev proposed on Monday [21 March] a new framework of 
talks by the United States, Russia and China with North Korea 
over its suspected development of nuclear weapons, Japanese 
officials said. Kozyrev disclosed the idea during a meeting 
with Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata in Moscow, the 
officials said. 
  Kozyrev also urged Pyongyang to abide by controls on nuclear 
facilities as imposed under the international nuclear safeguard 
agreement, they said. He argued that all controls should be 
abided by through inspections by experts from the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), the officials said. 
  High-level talks between the U.S. and North Korea have 
stalled in the wake of the IAEA's report that its inspection of 
Pyongyang's nuclear facilities had been obstructed and the 
collapse of the dialogue between North and South Korea. The IAEA 
adopted a resolution Monday to refer North Korea's refusal of 
full inspections of its nuclear facilities to the United Nations 
Security Council. 

</TEXT>

