<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Japanese Foreign Minister Hata's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Japanese Official on Territories </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103161694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1438 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Japan will continue to make efforts to ensure a 
resolution to the territorial dispute, the conclusion of a peace 
agreement and complete normalization of relations with Russia, 
director of the Japanese Foreign Ministry's international press 
department Seiji Morimoto stated during a briefing in Moscow on 
Monday. 
  He said that this position was set forth by Japanese Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata during his talks with Russia's Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin on Monday morning. To quote 
Morimoto, the Japanese side emphasized that the declaration 
signed in Tokyo last December by the Russian president and the 
Japanese prime minister creates a basis for broadening political 
dialogue between the two countries. 
  The Japanese diplomat also said that Japan would continue to 
support the Russian reforms and coordinate its moves with the 
G-7. During the talks Chernomyrdin and Hata stressed that Russia 
and Japan could jointly tackle major international problems. 
  Morimoto also said that the talks with the Russian prime 
minister had convinced Japan that relations with Japan were one 
of the priority aspects of Russia's foreign policy. "Neighbors 
are not chosen. As neighbors, Russia and Japan must cooperate," 
he said. 
  He pointed out that the Japanese foreign minister was 
satisfied with the discussion of the territorial issue. The 
Russian prime minister confirmed Russia's adherence to the Tokyo 
declaration and stated that a time would come when the 
territorial problems would be solved. 
  "This problem is very complicated and we are well aware that 
it cannot be solved at one go," said Morimoto. He also 
announced that Hata had invited Chernomyrdin to visit Japan this 
year. In Chernomyrdin [as received] invited Hata to visit 
Moscow. The dates of the visit will be coordinated through 
diplomatic channels. 
  Russia's possible admission to the G-7 was not discussed in 
detail, said Morimoto. Japan believes, however, that G-7 should 
broaden cooperation with Russia. "Such an initiative must come 
from Italy, because it currently chairs the G-7 and is the 
organizer of the forthcoming summit in Naples. Let us hope that 
this problem will be solved," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

