<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Japanese Foreign Minister Hata's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kozyrev, Hata Comment on Talks </H4>
<F P=102> LD2103160994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1438 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy, and others] 
  [Text] Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev believes 
that this summer the G-7 summit in Naples will discuss the 
gradual transformation of the G-7 into a G-8, because Russia 
will join full-scale discussions of the political problems. He 
made the statement Monday following the talks with Japanese 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata. 
  Kozyrev said he had discussed the problem with Hata. The 
Japanese side reacted positively, he said. 
  Kozyrev said that in Moscow, on the initiative of the 
Japanese side, the issue was discussed on signing a peace treaty 
which would include the territorial problem. "We do not give up 
on the problem. It will be discussed in detail on the basis of 
the Tokyo Declaration at the talks to be held by deputy foreign 
ministers, he said. 
  Kozyrev said that the territorial problem is not the sole 
issue in the Russian-Japanese talks. We have discussed 
bilateral and international problems and agreed to raise the 
level of economic cooperation; to work on, before the visit to 
Moscow by Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, the draft 
agreement on supporting small and medium business; and to 
continue the talks on strategic stability, he said. We also 
discussed the cases of violations along the Russian border by 
Japanese fishermen and agreed to cooperate in solving the 
problem. 
  For his part, Hata said that Kozyrev had handed over to him 
a 
personal message from Russian President Yeltsin, who invited 
Japanese Prime Minister Hosokawa to visit Moscow. The date of 
the visit will be set following the consultations with the 
Russian side, said Hata. 
  Hata spoke in support of the earliest signing of a peace 
treaty. But first we need to settle the territorial problem 
which is impossible without the support of the Russian and 
Japanese peoples, he said. 
  He said that Japan gives its backing to the course of 
reforms 
in Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

