<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second Stage of Japanese Aid Program Starts in Far East </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203060694 Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network in Russian 0815 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2203060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Pacific Ocean" Program] </F>
  [Text] The second stage of the large-scale Japanese 
humanitarian action has begun in the Far East. About 2,000 
tonnes of foodstuffs have been delivered here, including 
vegetable oils and canned meat, dairy, and fruit products which 
will be sold to the population at moderate prices. This 
long-term campaign is being conducted within the framework of an 
intergovernmental memorandum on urgent Japanese humanitarian 
assistance to the Russian Federation. 
  The first stage was carried out during the spring of last 
year. The money raised helped purchase modern medical equipment 
and equip medical institutions. This year it will be used to 
implement the program of social assistance to invalids. It 
should be noted that all stages of the humanitarian action are 
being strictly monitored not only by Russian social protection 
services but by the Japanese side as well. During the 27 
March-4 April period a group of experts from the Japanese 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs will carry out a working tour of the 
Far East. The aim is to evaluate the effectiveness of the 
assistance in the region and to determine the best way of 
rendering it in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

