<H3> <TI>   Karasin Outlines Position on North Korean Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203094794 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
0900 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2203094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Announcer] Head of the Foreign 
Ministry information department Grigoriy Karasin commented on 
the Russian position on this issue for us. 
  [Karasin] We would very much not like to bring the situation 
to a head, or to sanctions. Evidently the necessity has arisen 
to look at the situation attentively and discuss it with our 
partners. In particular the Russian and Japanese foreign 
ministers discussed this issue yesterday. And we have to find a 
quick, effective, and possibly even unusual solution to this 
problem. 
  [Announer] Can Russia, bearing in mind her recent successes 
in foreign policy, become an intermediary in the dialogue 
between Pyongyang and the countries of the West? Here is 
Grigoriy Karasin once again. 
  [Karasin] To be honest, I am not going to lay all my cards 
on 
the table. I just want to say that the appropriate senior 
Foreign Ministry employees have left for Vienna and are taking 
part in the discussions of this problem there. They return to 
Moscow tomorrow. We will take a close look at all possiblities 
and all approaches, and naturally we will act with energy. 

</TEXT>

