<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Downplays Conflict On DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2103162794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 22 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2103162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleksandr Platkovskiy: "Pyongyang Ready for War, </F>
But Moscow Hopes That Kim Il-song Is Bluffing"] 
  [Excerpts] The conflict concerning the DPRK's nuclear 
program has again entered an unpredictable, volatile stage after 
the North Koreans threatened to quit the nuclear weapons 
nonproliferation treaty and "commit Seoul to the flames." But 
all Moscow can do is observe events from the sidelines. 
  International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] experts who have 
returned after verification work at suspect facilities in the 
DPRK were unable to confirm that this secretive country is not 
carrying out work to create its own nuclear weapons. They did 
not manage to get into the radiochemical laboratory, where it is 
suspected that plutonium is possibly being produced for military 
needs. The IAEA Board of Governors will give the final verdict 
and will possibly raise the question of economic sanctions 
against the DPRK for discussion by the UN Security Council. 
[passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, in this situation Moscow prefers to refrain from 
making any statements. At least until the IAEA's final position 
becomes clear. As IZVESTIYA was informed by the Russian Foreign 
Ministry, the situation is not as serious as reports might 
indicate. At any rate, our diplomats still hope that the matter 
will not get as far as a discussion of the sanctions question by 
the Security Council. 
  So far Moscow has remained outside the circle of active 
participants in the conflict because it lacks any opportunities 
to influence the North Koreans' position. Despite the fact that 
the Treaty on Friendship and Cooperation between the USSR and 
the DPRK is still in force, just like the article providing for 
military aid in the case of aggression against the DPRK, the 
North Koreans regard this document merely as a scrap of paper. 
  But if the matter does get as far as a discussion of 
sanctions by the Security Council, our experts believe that 
Russian diplomats' main task will be not to back the North 
Koreans into a corner. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-16996 </DOCNO>
