<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Sees Partnership Signing Delayed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1903085094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 19 Mar 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1903085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Dmitriy Gornostayev report under the "Cooperation" rubric: </F>
"Special Conditions for Moscow. NATO's Partnership With Russia 
Will Differ From its Relations With East European Countries"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Yuriy Ushakov, director of 
the Russian Foreign Ministry All-European Cooperation 
Department, has said to your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA correspondent 
that as it is going to sign the "Partnership for Peace" plan, 
Russia sees it as a stage on the way to reaching a wide-ranging 
agreement on cooperation with NATO that could be contemplated 
both within the "Partnership for Peace" concept and outside it. 
The program itself is in principle acceptable for Russia at 
this stage as "a compromise that has come about under the 
influence of a number of factors." Moscow does not want to 
approach it from a formal, symbolic point of view that 
characterizes the stances of a number of East European countries 
that confuse a NATO membership card with a credit card to borrow 
money from Western banks. Russia's partnership, however, will 
be different from the cliches of its former Warsaw Pact allies. 
It is essential to take into account its weight on the 
international scene, its status of a nuclear power, and the 
importance of relations between the two partners -- Russia 
itself and NATO. The North Atlantic Alliance, however, is 
preoccupied with the search for a formula that, while formally 
not recognizing Russia's privileged status within "Partnership 
for Peace," would still enable them to foster a special 
cooperation. A number of NATO experts talk about the "16+1" 
formula, which calls for special consultations between the 
Russian Federation and NATO. That is precisely what Russia 
wants. Special conditions will still have to be created for 
Moscow. 
  There is yet another reservation: Many Russian and foreign 
mass media have interpreted Grachev's words as meaning that 
Russia would definitely sign the "Partnership for Peace" in 
March. Officials on Smolenskaya Square [Foreign Ministry] 
clarify: "Maybe in late March, maybe later." The latter is 
more likely. This has been caused by the need to complete the 
drafting of documents, to wind up interdepartmental 
consultations, and to solve a number of technical problems. 
There are two candidates for signing on the Russian side: 
Kozyrev and Grachev. The site of the signing is already known 
-- Brussels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

