<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin `Pleased' with Talks with IMF Director </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803175094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1454 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1803175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin had talks 
Friday with Michel Camdessus, managing director of the 
International Monetary Fund, on making the second part of the 
nearly $1.5 Bn systems credit available to Russia. 
  Chernomyrdin told journalists after the meeting that he was 
pleased with its results and intended to meet Camdessus again 
Friday and Saturday. "Meanwhile the experts will do their bit," 
he said. He added that IMF experts wanted to have a better 
insight into the Russian economy. 
  Valeriy Grishin, first deputy director of the government's 
press service, told INTERFAX that IMF officials were troubled by 
the recent remarks made by the Liberal Democratic Party leader 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy who doubted the indices mentioned in the 
budget draft. Zhirinovskiy accused the cabinet of promising 
unduly high revenues and unduly low spending. 
  Grishin said that Chernomyrdin had asked the IMF delegation 
directly if the IMF was willing to help Russia and added that 
the Russian government did not depend on the Fund's support for 
its success. Grishin recalled that the Russian cabinet had met 
the conditions made by the IMF earlier by holding monthly 
inflation below the 16 to 18 percent mark. According to 
Grishin, the IMF officials had admitted this. Now the IMF 
wanted to verify the budget indices, thus making a new 
condition. Grishin said that the Western experts and their 
Russian colleagues would be given this opportunity. 
  Camdessus will also meet with Russian Economy Minister 
Aleksandr Shokhin Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
